<HEAD>Stones Pay Per View Concert Tops North American Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rolling Stones capped the next-to-last show of their 32-city North American tour with a guest appearance by British blues guitarist <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Clapton </PERSON> for the band's pay-per-view concert Tuesday night The capacity crowd of 16,000 at Convention Hall roared when the bearded <PERSON> Clapton </PERSON> stepped to center stage for two bluesy solos during `` Little Red Rooster.'' The Stones' lead singer, <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>, in turquoise shirt, black jeans and silver-studded belt, then joined the <PERSON> Clapton </PERSON> on harmonica. <PERSON> Clapton </PERSON>, wearing a black leather jacket and white T-shirt, was making his first appearance with the Stones on the current tour. The pay-per-view concert Tuesday night was to be seen in 13.5 million homes and heard on about 150 radio stations, promoters said. The concert, the second of three scheduled at 16,000-seat Convention Hall, also featured appearances by vocalist <PERSON> Axl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> and guitarist <PERSON> Izzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stradlin </PERSON> of Guns' n' Roses and by 71-year-old Southern blues guitar legend <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON>. Rose and <PERSON> Stradlin </PERSON>, introduced by <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> as having come `` all the way East to get their tattooes touched up,'' sang, `` Salt of the Earth'' with the original bad boys of rock' n' roll. <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> seemed more animated Tuesday night, playing up to the television cameras, leading middle-aged fans through the new lyrics of `` Terrifying'' and swaying to `` Ruby Tuesday'' with fans born after it was first recorded in 1967. Tickets for each of the Stones' concerts Sunday, Tuesday and Wednesday in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> cost $ 38.50, $ 150 and $ 250. The Stones, who have been performing since 1962, opened the tour Aug. 31 at Veterans Stadium in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The group took off Monday to celebrate guitarist <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>' 46th birthday <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurnit </PERSON>, the president of Set Pay Per View, the show's distributor to cable companies, said the suggested retail price for the concert was $ 24.95, but added that some cable companies were charging $ 19.95 <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> said the live televised performance would inject just the boost needed for the Stones at the end of their first tour since 1981. `` You get wound up for live TV ... especially at the end of a tour,'' said <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>, 46.
