<HEAD>Leader Of Failed Homeland Coup Gets 18-Year Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A soldier who led a failed coup attempt in one of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s nominally independent black homelands has been sentenced to 18 years in prison for high treason. Warrant Officer <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Phiri </PERSON> was the last of 142 soldiers to be sentenced for their roles in a February 1988 coup attempt in <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>, one of four tribal homelands designated independent by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but not recognized abroad. The other defendants, convicted last month of treason or terrorism, were sentenced Monday and Tuesday to prison terms ranging from 2 to 10 years. The coup was crushed by South African commandos, who freed homeland president <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangope </PERSON> from captivity at a soccer stadium and arrested the rebels, all members of the homeland army. <ORGANIZATION> Bophuthatswana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> M.W. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Phiri </PERSON> was `` a danger to society'' who had allowed <PERSON> Mangope </PERSON> to be ill-treated during the coup attempt and had ordered his rebels to fire on the homes of homeland Cabinet ministers.
