<HEAD>Savannah Leaders Praise Slain Alderman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mail Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, the alderman and lawyer assassinated by a mail bomb, is being remembered as an easygoing, generous man whose community affairs work made people `` believe they can make a difference.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, whom even new acquaintances called `` <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON>,'' died Monday when a package containing an explosive and nails blew up at his law office. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> and Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> had planned to attend a meeting that evening at the lawyer's church to discuss how blacks could fight drugs in their neighborhoods. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was black. The 42-year-old attorney was the second victim in a rash of mail bombs in the South. A package bomb killed 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> on Saturday. A mail bomb found at the federal courthouse in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> was disarmed Monday. A parcel bomb mailed to the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, office was disarmed Tuesday. On Tuesday, <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>'s legislative offices were closed in mourning. <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> `` was a warm, kind person, always with a smile on his face and a hand out to help.'' `` He meant the future to <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, he gave to the community in such a selfless way that he made people just believe they can make a difference,'' said <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. At a news conference, city leaders said they believed <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s involvement with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, which he represented in a school desegregation case, was related to his death <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was an active member of his church and was worked to help the homeless. Friends said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s political activity was not the kind that would be expected to generate murderous enemies. `` I've known him a very long time, and he is not the kind of guy I would think would be a target of such an action,'' said Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadsden </PERSON>. `` He was easygoing and went about his business.'' Longtime friend <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivers </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> took part in civil rights protests until he went off to college. `` Then he came back, got into politics and his time began to get tight.'' <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> had been a city councilman for eight years, but had served on other government and community boards his entire adult life. As city transit authority chairman 10 years ago, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> led a move to provide transportation for the poor and the elderly. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, one of the first black students to attend <ORGANIZATION> Savannah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in the 1960s, represented the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> in the long-running <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> schools desegregation case. The 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in October that the city's magnet-school plan was appropriate for desegregation. Neither city nor school officials knew whether the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> was planning to appeal, and NACCP head <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> could not be reached for comment. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>, and three daughters. <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said city officials would start a fund for <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s family. <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> said a local business, All-American Builders, had already donated a $ 1,000 reward for information in the case. `` We are sure the <ORGANIZATION> Savannah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will not quit until they come to some conclusion,'' <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` Meanwhile, the fund gives people a way to prove their love for <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON>.''
