<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Force Bjt   12-20 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Force, Bjt,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Only Violence Can Bring Down Ceausescu</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In contrast to the largely peaceful changes in other Eastern European countries, President <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> appears determined to use force to defend his hard-line regime. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, 71, the most senior Soviet bloc leader after 24 years in power, has said reform-minded Communists elsewhere have betrayed their people by refusing to defend Marxist orthodoxy. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s refusal to embrace change has isolated him from all his <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> allies. Some analysts say he is seeking stronger ties with rigid Communist systems similarly opposed to political reform, particularly <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. His leadership is based on a family dynasty with some 40 relatives reportedly placed in key state and party jobs. His wife <PERSON> Elena </PERSON>, virtual second-in-command in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, is a Politburo member and first vice premier. One of <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s brothers, <PERSON> Ilie </PERSON>, is an army general and deputy defense minister. Another brother, <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Andruta </PERSON>, is a police general and deputy interior minister and another brother, <PERSON> Ion </PERSON>, is in charge of economic planning. His youngest son, <PERSON> Nicu </PERSON>, 39, is a Politburo candidate member and party chief of <LOCATION> Sibiu </LOCATION> region in southern <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> is a showcase for any repressive totalitarian state. The harsher the repression, the more violent the public upheaval it brings about and the greater the desire to take revenge on leaders,'' <PERSON> Ion </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratiu </PERSON>, chairman of the London-based <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of Free Romanians, said Monday. Since he became party leader in 1965, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> has exercised absolute power and carried out a foreign policy independent of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. While that maverick stance won him praise and credits from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> kept Romanians under iron-fisted control. Now, with reform ascendent in the rest of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact, the harsh Romanian stand draws condemnation from abroad. About 30,000 coal miners went on strike in the <LOCATION> Jiu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in 1977 and 10,000 workers demonstrated in the city of <LOCATION> Brasov </LOCATION> in 1987 demanding freedom, better living conditions and <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s ouster. Police arrested hundreds of demonstrators and their leaders disappeared. An extensive secret police force keeps strict control on religious and political expression, and dissent is quickly crushed, making chances for peaceful change in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> seem remote. But poverty and despair engendered by economic problems and political repressions could cause people to risk direct confrontations with armed forces, as in <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION> now. Unlike recent protests in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, witnessed and reported by the Western media, demonstrations in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> have taken place well outside the public eye. The Western reporters permitted into the country in recent years have been kept under close watch, and police have detained journalists and even diplomats attempting to visit the country's few dissidents <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> has closed its borders and barred most foreigners from entering the country in an apparent attempt to prevent the spread of news about the <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION> protest, the largest demonstration against <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s policies since the <LOCATION> Brasov </LOCATION> riots. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> has little tradition of democratic rule. After five centuries under the Ottoman Turks, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> won independence in 1877, becoming first a monarchy, then, during the Second World War, an ally of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. The last monarch, King <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, was forced to abdicate in December 1947 under threat of civil war and pressure from the Kremlin and its Romanian Communist allies.
</TEXT>
