<HEAD>Art Auction Houses More Than Double Yearly Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two leading art auctioneers are reporting more than doubled yearly sales with the market for impressionist, modern, and contemporary art racing to dizzying heights. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s fine art auctioneers on Tuesday reported worldwide sales in 1989 of $ 2.9 billion, a 61 percent increase on 1988. And <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s reported worldwide sales in 1989 of $ 2.2 billion, a 69 percent increase. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ainslie </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement: `` The opportunities for forming major collections have never been better as the flow of significant works onto the market is stronger than we have ever witnessed. `` More collectors are participating in our business, and balanced competition from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has become a regular feature of the international art auction market.'' <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s said auctions of Impressionist, modern and contemporary art worldwide during its autumn sales season this year alone accounted for $ 797 million of overall sales. Lord <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Christie </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement: `` The strength of the market has been underpinned by the growth in world wealth and the emergence of new buyers into the arena. This has caused a change in the emphasis of the market place, which has become more international.'' He said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> has become the leading sales center.
