<HEAD>Social Security Pushing for Faster Catastrophic Refunds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> is supporting a plan under which the government early next year would mail monthly refunds to millions of elderly people overcharged for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> premiums. If the plan goes through, Social Security beneficiaries who unavoidably will be overcharged by about $ 5.30 a month for their Medicare coverage early in 1990 will be simultaneously issued monthly refund checks. The overcharges are the result of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' late action in repealing <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>'s catastrophic health-care program. Social Security contends its computers ca n't be adjusted by January to halt withholding of the extra Medicare premium for catastrophic coverage. As a result, nearly 27 million Social Security beneficiaries who have <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> premiums deducted directly from their benefit checks are expected to be overcharged from January through May. Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> said Tuesday a panel of experts convened by the agency to study the problem suggested issuing monthly or bimonthly refund checks to offset the overcharges, or sending out lump-sum refunds late in the spring. Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which actually issues Social Security checks, reported that lump-sum refunds were the most feasible option and that monthly refund checks would be `` much worse than the other two scenarios.'' However, Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> did not expressly rule out the possibility of mailing monthly refunds, so she will `` send back a signal that that would be our preferred option.'' She said she would ask <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> to advise her on whether it can provide monthly checks. `` That option ... appears to be the best way to get money back as quickly as possible,'' Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said in an interview. `` My purpose has been to try to make the beneficiaries whole. They should not have to pay for this problem. The question is how can we get them this money.'' <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency has been meeting with Social Security `` to identify the most expeditious way to achieve the refunds. At this particular point, nothing has been decided.'' Social Security initially had said it probably would issue the refunds in lump sums late in the spring. Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s statement that she would push for monthly refunds came on the same day that two congressmen sent President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a letter asking him to support that option. Reps. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said retirees should not have to pay _ even temporarily _ for a program that wo n't exist `` For seniors, this is n't just a matter of principle _ it's a matter of meeting rent payments, buying food and paying utilities,'' <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimated the cost of issuing monthly refunds at $ 25 million to $ 30 million, and said the first refund checks could be in the mail by February. Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said each extra monthly mailing would cost about $ 10 million.
