<HEAD>Many Long Distance Phone Rates to Drop in 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many long distance telephone rates to points in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad will be going down after the first of the year, the three major long distance companies say. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> filed reductions with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> said they will take action to remain competitive. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> says it has about 70 percent of the long distance market, as measured by interstate and intrastate revenues. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> is No. 2 with more than 10 percent. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> claims 7 to 8 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T reductions will take effect Jan. 1, barring an unusual action by the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to block them. The company said the reductions were taken in line with an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> price cap which has been reduced because local telephone companies are charging long distance companies less for access to customers' lines <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's submission to the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> called for $ 300 million a year in reductions on interstate and international long distance services used primarily by residential and small business customers. Other categories of service used by businesses, such as private lines and 800 and 900 numbers, are not affected. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON> said the No. 2 long distance company also will reduce its rates to pass on the savings in local telephone company charges. `` We will remain competitive with them,'' he said. `` I do n't know how much our total cost savings will be.'' <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>'s counterpart at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pence </PERSON>, said, `` We are reviewing the filing and we intend to remain competitive.'' The company said price reductions will apply to its `` Reach Out <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' and optional long distance plans as well as to basic long distance service. A 10-minute call during daytime hours on a weekday, to anywhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, will cost $ 2.50 or less, a decrease of 1.3 percent on the average, the company said. Some of the increases would be greater. For example, a 10-minute daytime call from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which now costs $ 2.30, would decline to $ 2.20. Daytime hours are 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. local time Monday through Friday. In the evening, the rate for a call to anywhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will drop by an average of 2 percent, the company said. An evening call from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, which now costs $ 1.67 for 10 minutes, would be $ 1.58. The evening period is 5 p.m. to 11 p.m. Sunday through Friday. Weekend rates are in effect all day Saturday and until 5 p.m. on Sunday and the same rates apply from 11 p.m. to 8 a.m. Sunday through Friday. These rates will not change. The maximum for such a call is $ 1.32 for 10 minutes within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the company said. Discounts for subscribers to the Reach Out <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> 24-hour plan will be increased from 5 percent to 10 percent on weekday calls and from 20 to 25 percent on evening calls. Under Reach Out <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the evening period is 5 p.m. to 10 p.m. Sunday through Friday. International calls from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mainland to 25 of the most frequently called countries and overseas areas will be slashed by $ 104 million. The reductions will vary from country to country and the countries will include <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. A five-minute call from anywhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> between 2 and 8 p.m., now $ 8.72 at the standard rate prevailing in those hours, will drop to $ 8.07. A similar call to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> between 1 and 6 p.m., when discount rates are in effect for such calls, will decline from $ 4.21 to $ 3.99. Calls to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will decline from 2 to 20 percent, depending on the time and the city from which the call is placed. A five-minute call from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>, now $ 7.90 at the standard rate, will drop to $ 5.90. Five minutes from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, now $ 6.15, will cost $ 5.55. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T said the reduction will be the company's 10th since 1984 and would bring total rate decreases to 40 percent in the six years since the breakup of the Bell System.
