<HEAD>Leftist Bitterly Concedes Defeat in Presidential Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Socialist <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Inacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lula </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> conceded defeat in the presidential election, but he accused conservative victor <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> of deception and pledged to build an opposition `` shadow government.'' Election officials announced Tuesday that <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>, a champion of free-market policies, had won Sunday's balloting. `` <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> is the winner and that must be respected. But <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> was the big loser in the election, gained through lies and falsehoods,'' <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> told a news conference in <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>. `` He will govern in favor of big business, the armed forces, and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies will form a shadow government to prevent Collor de Mello from committing abuses.'' With 96.7 percent of the ballots tallied, <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reconstruction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had 33,898,190 votes, or 42.7 percent, compared with 30,546,337, or 38.5 percent, for <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The rest of the votes were abstentions or nullified ballots. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Rezek </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that was supervising the tally, said <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> would be declared the winner Wednesday, but an official announcement would only be made Dec. 29. The election was the first direct vote for president in 29 years. Current president <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> was selected in an <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> vote strongly influenced by the right-wing military government that ran the country between 1964 and 1985. <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> has been secluded in his <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION> mansion. Aides say he will only address the nation after election officials proclaim him the winner. TV Globo, the nation's largest television network, ran a previously taped interview with the president-elect Tuesday night in which <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> promised a government with `` dignity, austerity and character.'' The new president's first challenge will be harnassing inflation racing at over 1,500 percent this year amid growing poverty. <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>'s campaign advisers have told the press he will seek to heal the wounds from the electoral campaign and call for a government of `` national unity.'' However, the wounds run deep. In the campaign's final week, <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>'s campaign made vicious personal attacks on <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> and said his party wanted to impose a communist dictatorship in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. `` I would never sit at the same table with <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>. The low blows he used caused me to lose all respect for him,'' <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> said at the Tuesday press conference. He said <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>, scheduled to take office on March 15, will face strong opposition from labor unions and six leftist parties. During the electoral campaign, <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> promised to end inflation, privatize state-run firms, reduce the size of government, and sell <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister's mansions to reduce the public deficit. He also won the vote of a great part of the uneducated rural poor by pledging to increase spending for housing, education and health care. To realize these promises, <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> must seek allies in the country's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The new president's party has 24 senators and representatives, only 3 percent of those in congress. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> said his party would back <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> if he sincerely attempted to carry out social reforms in this polarized society, where the richest 1 percent receives almost half the national income. `` But I'm afraid his call for national unity is nothing more than a trick to keep the working class quiet,'' he said.
