<HEAD>Construction Companies Pay in Bid-Rigging Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government is being paid $ 32.7 million by 99 Japanese companies to settle bid-rigging charges that officials say raised construction costs of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base by 25 percent. The cartel of 140 companies had bid on construction of the base at <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Fair Trade Commission, which administers that country's antitrust laws, earlier had fined 69 companies 1.5 percent of the value of each company's contract, for a total of $ 2.2 million, and had warned 70 unsuccessful bidders not to continue in the bid-rigging arrangement Some companies offered to negotiate a settlement as a result of threats of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government lawsuit in the Japanese courts and also in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts against 26 companies also doing business in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the department said. The settlement, which involved 99 firms, was negotiated in November, the agency said. Japanese construction companies frequently collaborate on bids in a system called `` dango'' where the bidders decide who gets the winning bid. The 140 companies bidding for <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts at <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION> formed an association in 1984 that called itself `` Seiyukai,'' or `` Friends of the Stars,'' a reference to the American flag. The association dissolved in 1987 when the companies became aware that they were under investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerson </PERSON>, assistant attorney general in charge of the civil division of the department, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would pursue `` available remedies,'' including possible lawsuits in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or both countries, against construction companies that did not join the settlement. `` We are pleased to have been able to reach a just result through the Japanese legal process,'' <PERSON> Gerson </PERSON> said.
