<HEAD>Romanian Unrest May be Beginning of End for Ceausescu, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, bgng: The current xxx to CORRECT that Brasov
is not near Timisoara or Arad.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The unrest in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> may be the beginning of the end for strongman <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, who was hailed 24 years ago as a Soviet bloc maverick but is increasingly denounced for his repressive policies. `` We are definitely in the twilight of the <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> era,'' said <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Larabee </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The Soviet foreign minister and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> both condemned <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s use of violence to crush demonstrations in the Romanian city of <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION>, where according to some reports as many as 400 people died. But <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, who has ruled <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> with an iron hand since 1965, `` is going to be a harder nut to crack'' than communist leaders swept from power in the Soviet bloc nations of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a specialist in East European affairs at the <ORGANIZATION> RAND </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> has been a maverick in the Soviet camp for decades _ boycotting <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact exercises, trading with the West against <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> wishes and most recently balking at the democratic reforms of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Although <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> may be able to survive in the short term, his days seem numbered, said <PERSON> Larabee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and other analysts. `` This incident or some other might open up an explosion of popular dissent, or some group in the leadership, such as the military, may decide to get rid of him. Sometime or another, something has to give,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Garthoff </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and now a senior scholar at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The current unrest in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> began as a reaction to repressions against the Hungarian minority in the nearby cities of <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arad </LOCATION>, along with the more distant city of <LOCATION> Brasov </LOCATION>, but reports indicate that ethnic Romanians may have joined the demonstrations. Experts say that is bad news for <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> was once a favorite of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leaders because he refused to allow Romanian troops to join <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> military maneuvers, was the only Soviet bloc leader to maintain full relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and traded with Western nations against the wishes of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. In 1969, then-President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> in the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state visit to a Soviet bloc nation. <PERSON> Ceausesu </PERSON>'s widely reported human rights abuses chilled U.S.-Romanian relations, however, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year withdrew trade favors from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, costing that nation as much as $ 250 million annually. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> harshly criticized <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Tuesday. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> condemns the brutal use of police force by the Romanian government against protesters in <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION> and other cities,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said that if the reports of bloodshed were true, `` I can only express my very profound regret. We are categorically opposed to the use of force.'' <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> has been a maverick since the late 1950s when <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s predecessor rejected a <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> plan to more closely integrate the Romanian economy into Soviet bloc by selling <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and its allies oil and other natural resources. Instead, the Romanians sold their oil to the West and used the money to industrialize. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> became party leader in 1965 and refused to allow Romanian forces to take part in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact exercises. He was the only <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leader to refuse to take part in the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. He denounced the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979 and refused to join the Soviet bloc boycott of the 1984 Olympic Games in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Throughout that period, the Romanians took advantage of the Sino-Soviet dispute, playing <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> off against <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. As reforms have swept <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> has kept close ties with conservatives in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and counts as his closest allies hardline communist leaders in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said.
