<HEAD>Eighteen State Legislatures Targeted by Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Statehouse races in 18 states will be targeted next year by Democrats who hope to control state legislatures when congressional districts are redrawn for the 1990s. Democrats will try to raise $ 3 million to help candidates for the legislatures in those states next year, <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>, who heads the party's Project 500 program, said Tuesday. Democrats are particularly concerned with states likely to gain or lose congressional districts as a result of population shifts that will come to light in the 1990 census. They are also focusing on states where the majority's grip in the state legislature is tenuous. The targeted states are <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. Democrats now control 36 state Houses and 32 state Senates, while Republicans control 12 Houses and 17 Senates. They share power in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> has a nonpartisan bicameral legislature.
