<HEAD>Sears, Government Settle Insulation Ads Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to pay a $ 100,000 civil penalty to settle a dispute with the government over insulation ads, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> or its representatives had failed to include details on the insulation's heat resistance when it promoted the thickness and price of the product. The ads ran within the last five years. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to create an advertisement designed to educate consumers about home insulation, especially the importance of having heat-resistance information when making a purchase, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` The violations were technical in nature and did not result in any consumer complaints,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` There was no misrepresentation or deception involved.'' The settlement must be approved by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said the consent decree does not constitute admission of a law violation. The penalty is paid to the government, not consumers.
