<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says it's upgrading an investigation of a possible steering deficiency in the 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beretta </ORGANIZATION>. The agency also said Tuesday it was beginning probes of reported explosions in the heating systems of <ORGANIZATION> Coachmen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> recreational vehicles and of cruise control failures in the Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable. The agency said it was stepping up its Beretta probe from a preliminary evaluation, which involves mostly paperwork, to an engineering analysis, in which the possibly defective parts are examined. Such investigations can lead to recalls or can be dismissed if engineers decide there is no widespread safety problem.
