<HEAD>Dollar Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index regained its early losses today while the dollar edged up against the yen on news that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops had been sent to seize Panamaniam strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The dollar closed at 144.23 yen, up 0.43 yen from Tuesday's close of 143.80 yen It started the day's trading at 143.92 yen and ranged between 143.90-144 .25 yen Earlier trading was quiet as market players made small position adjustments ahead of the Christmas holidays. But the dollar edged up later in the afternoon on news that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces were attacking <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s military headquarters in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said a trader with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ordered troops into action following several days of tension triggered by the shooting death in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> on Saturday of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officer. `` Japanese market players were waiting to see how the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market reacts to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> situation tonight,'' the trader said. Participants were also held back by uncertainties over <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s discount rate increase, the trader added `` Although the government yesterday denied a hike any time soon, the market expects a 50 percent chance of a hike by the end of the year,'' the trader said. Local news reports speculated the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> might raise its key lending rate to commercial banks by 0.5 percent to 4.25 percent, but the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ