<HEAD>New York High Court Throws Out State Harassment Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 5th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s highest court ruled the state's harassment law unconstitutional, saying speech that may be abusive is still protected by the First Amendment The decision may spark challenges against such laws in other states, attorneys said. Civil rights advocates applauded the decision and said it would prevent police officers from arresting people, especially demonstrators, for using language that could be considered offensive. `` I think it's clear now that you ca n't prosecute someone for cursing someone out on the street,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The case involved a dispute in which a woman called a neighbor a bitch and her son a dog as they passed by her door. The woman, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Raymondville </LOCATION>, also allegedly threatened to `` beat the crap out of'' the woman. <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON>, 19, was sentenced to 15 days in jail and fined $ 50. On Tuesday, the state <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, in a 7-0 decision, threw out her conviction. It ruled 5-2 that the law was unconstitutional. The court said the harassment statute `` prohibits a substantial amount of constitutionally protected expression.'' Judge <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said the law needed to be undone `` because its continued existence presents a significant risk of prosecution for the mere exercise of free speech.'' `` Casual conversation may well be abusive and intended to annoy. So, too, may be light-hearted banter or the earnest expression of personal opinion or emotion,'' <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> said. `` But unless speech presents a clear and present danger of some serious substantial evil, it may neither be forbidden nor penalized.'' Most states have anti-harassment statutes similar in intent to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hellerstein </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and a specialist on the First Amendment, said the decision was bound to spur challenges in other states. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has not addressed the issue of whether words _ unless representing a direct threat to safety _ can constitute harassment, <PERSON> Hellerstein </PERSON> said. `` This should be a victory for all of us in protecting liberty,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasdon </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for the Homeless, of Tuesday's decision. `` We do n't want to become a society where people get intimidated for being creative or eccentric. `` I guess the standard now is ` fighting words,''' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON>, spokeswoman for state Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, who was on the losing end of the case. `` You can not say something that is going to incite someone to an immediate act of violence.'' <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON>'s words drew tears from her neighbor, <PERSON> Shelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON> denied using the language cited in the court case and said that the incident with <PERSON> Lazore </PERSON> stemmed from a feud over a boyfriend. <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON> said she was `` relieved'' that the case was over. <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballan </PERSON>, said that while the decision may expand freedom of speech, it could also have another impact. `` There are people who are quite obnoxious and are in the habit of using foul language,'' <PERSON> Ballan </PERSON> said. `` These people are going to feel like they can be as obnoxious as they wish. `` But those are the effects of freedom,'' he said. <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> District Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> did not return telephone calls. Prosecutors had maintained that <PERSON> Dietze </PERSON> stepped over the line of acceptable behavior and that the Constitution does n't apply to abusive language.
