<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scriptwriter <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON>, who was blacklisted during the <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> era and whose movie credits include `` El Cid,'' `` Back to <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION>,'' `` The Blue Max,'' and `` Z,'' has died. He was 79. <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON> died Friday after suffering a stroke. <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON>, a journalist, novelist and author of musical revues, began writing for the movies in 1943. He wrote or co-wrote the scripts of such films as `` The Boy With the Green Hair,'' `` Back to <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION>,'' `` El Cid,'' `` The Blue Max,'' `` Z,'' `` The Visit,'' `` The Fall of the Roman Empire'' and `` Heroes of Telemark.'' Some of the movies did not contain his screen credit because of the blacklist aimed at writers accused of being communist, said his wife, <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON> left the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1949 for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where his movie `` Christ in Concrete'' was being filmed. The movie, recently purchase by Home Box Office for release next year, went on to win awards at several European film festivals, but <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON> and his wife were told they were no longer welcome in <LOCATION> McCarthy-era </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. The government went on to revoke the Canadian-born <PERSON> Barzman </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship in 1954 Although the government restored his citizenship nine years later, he and his wife and seven children continued to life abroad until 1976. During that time he wrote novels and French and Italian films. His 1960 book `` Echo X'' won a Science Fiction Book-of-the-Month Award. He was honored with a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Cinematheque film retrospective in 1982 and the French named him an officer of the Order of the Arts and Letters in 1985. A memorial service was scheduled for Jan. 7. Survivors include his wife, children and five grandchildren.
