<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Jan. 6 _ Nine launches and two helicopters from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Southern Command went to the southern outlet of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said it was a training mission; the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> called it intimidation. March 1 _ One Panamanian was killed and two were wounded when they stepped on unexploded munitions in a military zone, the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said. March 3 _ Panamanian soldiers held nine <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> school buses carrying 100 children for three hours on grounds the buses did not have proper license plates. Aug. 8 _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces detained 20 Panamanians, including nine soldiers who had tried to block maneuvers on U.S.-controlled territory, the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> reported. They were were released a few hours later. Aug. 9 _ Southern Command tanks blocked the entrance to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amador </LOCATION> and helicopters flew over the area at the southern end of the canal. The <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said it acted because <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> detained two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers. The Americans were exchanged for two Panamanians detained by the Americans that day. Aug. 17 _ The <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> conducted maneuvers at 11 installations along the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they were enforcing their rights under the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties; <LOCAT