<HEAD>Decision to Strike Against Noriega Made on Sunday, White House Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made up his mind Sunday to launch the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strike against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, barely 24 hours after the slaying of an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> officer outside <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s military headquarters in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the White House said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials kept their plans secret until Tuesday evening when news organizations began reporting heavy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military flights into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has 12,000 troops based to protect the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Even as the Pentagon was preparing the effort to capture <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and allow Panamanian opposition leaders to take over the government, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went as planned Tuesday evening to a White House Christmas party for 300 friends, administration officials, White House staff and reporters. The president maintained silence Sunday when asked for his reaction to the killing of the unarmed <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant, who was trying to escape a Panamanian <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> checkpoint after a wrong turn brought him and three other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers close to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s headquarters. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, in an early morning briefing today announcing the move against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` has been considering this matter for several days.'' He said the president `` was quite disturbed'' by the killing of the Marine officer and harassment of a naval officer and his wife by Panamanian soldiers at the same checkpoint. `` The president reviewed this issue with his national security advisers on Sunday afternoon. They considered options, developed a plan and the president made the basic decision to proceed with this action,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He added that there had been `` any number of meetings'' since Sunday, but emphasized, `` there really has not been any question about our willingness or our readiness to proceed since that time.'' The White House on Sunday deplored the killing of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and said the incident was a `` consequence'' of the outlaw <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> regime, imposed on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> against `` the will of the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people'' who voted in May to elect opposition leader <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> to the presidency. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s military commander and de facto ruler, nullified those elections. On Friday a legislature of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> cronies declared the country in a state of war against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and named <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> its `` maximum'' leader. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in an interview Monday with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and other wire services, expressed `` enormous frustration ... that the democratic system that was voted on in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was totally put down by force.'' He called the killing of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> `` an enormous outrage,'' and pointedly refused to rule out a military response. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had no public events on his schedule Tuesday except the Christmas party, where he and wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> gaily posed with each guest for pictures in front of an enormous tree, decorated with dolls from children's stories and fables. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stayed to hear an Army chorus sing carols in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Room </LOCATION>, hoisting up 3-year-old granddaughter <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBlond </PERSON> in his arms for a better view and extending a hearty handshake to former White House press secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, wounded in the 1981 assassination attempt against former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. At the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, military public information officers also sought not to tip their hand. Most left their offices at the regular quitting time Tuesday evening. National Security Adviser <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, his deputy <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> and White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> all put in brief appearances at the Christmas party Tuesday night before shuttling back to their offices to wait for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strike. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stayed in the Oval Office until 4:05 a.m. EST, when he retired to his personal residence for a brief sleep before a 7 a.m. address to the nation from the Oval Office.
