<HEAD>Soldiers Dispatched to Panama From N.C., California</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT ORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers from the <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deployment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> at Fort Ord and from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, have been dispatched to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to help apprehend Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said today. `` Elements of the 7th Light Infantry Division ... have supplemented the 12,000 troops already in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Republican said in a telephone interview with <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> KNX </ORGANIZATION>. Troops from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION> were airlifted to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who praised President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for the decision to send to the Central American country. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is `` up to his eyeballs in the drug traffic,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who nullified his country's May elections, was indicted on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug trafficking charges in February 1988. The senator's comments followed the mobilization Tuesday night of an undetermined number of soliders from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ord </LOCATION>, about 80 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and their transfer, apparently to <ORGANIZATION> Travis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fairfield </LOCATION>. Soldiers of the 7th Infantry Division -LRB- Light -RRB-, which in some deployments includes artillery and aviation units, were ordered to report to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ord </LOCATION> for an `` emergency deployment readiness training exercise,'' some time Monday, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, public affairs officers for the Army. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, however, said that as a matter of policy, he could not comment on the number mobilized, their destination or their time of departure. By early today, military convoys were seen heading north on Interstate 680 toward <LOCATION> Fairfield </LOCATION>, according to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Highway Patrol. Nineteen buses and a truck loaded with soldiers arrived at <LOCATION> Travis </LOCATION> late Tuesday, according KCRA-TV in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>. More buses and trucks were reported going into the base about 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. But a base spokesman said he could not say where the soliders came from or where they were going. `` We can not comment on any military operations at this time,'' said Sgt. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Taranto </PERSON>. `` We ca n't comment on anything on the operation.'' <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> was enveloped in heavy fog, making flights difficult. Earlier Tuesday, C-141 planes were seen in the air around <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, home of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s 82nd Airborne division. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION> spokesmen would say only that <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units there were participating in a routine `` emergency deployment readiness exercise.'' Sgt. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Feibel </PERSON>, a spokesman for the division, said he had no information on reports that some of the division had left <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>.
