<HEAD>Illegal Immigrants Fighting U.S. Government With Fifth Amendment
Cudgel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to RAISE legal argument; PICKS UP 17th graf
pvs, `One of ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-eight Latin American stablehands seized at a racetrack a year ago have taken the Fifth Amendment, challenging the government to prove they are illegal aliens. The government says it does n't have to to deport them. While illegal immigrants often do n't know their rights and prefer to go home rather than fight to stay, the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> cases are being regarded as a test of aliens' rights. The Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` is saying the government does n't have to come up with any evidence at all,'' said attorney <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Akram </PERSON>, who is orchestrating the aliens' defense. `` The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> has never brought a shred of evidence.'' `` It's a test of what the government burden is,'' said <PERSON> Akram </PERSON>, head of the Political Asylum Immigration Representation Project. `` Can the government haul anybody in off the streets and deport them if they refuse to answer questions based on their constitutional right not to do so? This is ridiculous.'' The defendants were among 83 Salvadoran, Mexican, Brazilian and Cuban stablehands rounded up Oct. 21, 1988 at <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Downs </LOCATION> during a dawn workout. Of the 83 people, six were found to be in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> lawfully. Some went home, while others admitted their illegal status and applied for asylum. The rest invoked their Fifth Amendment guarantee against self-incrimination at their deportation hearings. They want the government to prove they are here illegally. That is n't happening. Instead, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> attorneys are using an argument allowed in civil cases: that silence alone is ground for deportation. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigrants </ORGANIZATION>' Rights in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, called this development alarming `` It's disturbing if the immigration judge is making an inference from their silence that a person is an alien,'' he said. `` It reverses the whole idea that you are innocent until proven guilty.'' But an <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> official says the government is following precedent well-established in civil cases. `` The government does n't have to do any more,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Creppy </PERSON>, acting deputy counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` This is nothing new. The law is pretty clear in this matter. To me it's just a tactic to be able to stay here. Among the 38 aliens who invoked the Fifth Amendment was 21-year-old Salvadoran. His story is typical, said <PERSON> Akram </PERSON>, who requested the man be identified only as <PERSON> Jay </PERSON>. One of 10 children in a farming family, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> is from the mountains of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, where the army and the anti-government guerrillas have been waging war. He said both sides terrorize the inhabitants. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> told his attorney that by age 19, he was forced to act four times as a lookout on a guerrilla patrol. He knew better than to object after seeing a friend's face shot off for refusing to act as a guerrilla informant. Last year, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> fled, taking a bus to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. From there, he crossed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> border undetected and made his way from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Two months ago, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> had his day in Immigration Court. The attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> questioned him about where he came from and how he got here. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> replied in Spanish, `` I refuse to answer under the protection of the Fifth Amendment of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because my answer could incriminate me.'' The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> lawyer then asked the judge to deport him. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON>'s case is on appeal before the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON> said the use of the Fifth Amendment in deportation cases is rare but crucial. `` It's an important defense and it would be a tragic betrayal if this was taken away from aliens,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>' <PERSON> Creppy </PERSON> said the agency feels it will win. `` When you weigh the public interest versus the aliens' interest, this is a case that is clear,'' he said
</TEXT>
