<HEAD>Noriega Opponents Hope For Democracy; Supporters Urge Resistance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition politicians said they hoped the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> would bring democracy to the country, but supporters of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> called it `` genocide against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to `` remove the obstacle of the dictatorship was serious news, but we grasp it with hope,'' said <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON>, who was sworn in as first vice president shortly after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort began. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, who spoke on the radio, was a vice presidential candidate in the May 7 elections that were voided when results showed <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> opponents winning. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> was sworn in as president, and <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> was sworn in as vice president along with <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>. `` Tomorrow we will have the opportunity to celebrate the era of democracy with justice and freedom,'' <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> said. He urged the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, `` Do n't resist, accept instead the peace that they offer.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said the military action `` grieves us because it involves mourning and pain, but we pray to God that it will be the new awakening of this nation we love so much.'' <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said he hoped `` with this action we can achieve the Panamanian objectives, among them to immediately establish democracy with full respect for the will of the people.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> held an emergency meeting at an undisclosed site, said the government national radio, broadcasting as the national resistance network. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Duque </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s presidential candidate in the May 7 elections, called on all `` nationalist parties'' to join in the struggle. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has just committed the biggest error and is going to pay for that,'' he said. <PERSON> Rigoberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Paredes </PERSON>, another party leader, called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action an `` infamous invasion.'' He asked Latin American countries to tell the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` to stop this genocide against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' `` We are not going to surrender,'' he said. Not all those outraged by the invasion were <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> backers. A woman in Diablo, just south of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> base at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clayton </LOCATION>, said: `` This is humiliating. I feel completely impotent. My blood is boiling.'' She said she does not support <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> but also does not support the idea of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion. As she spoke, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trucks passed on a nearby road and fighting raged near Defense Forces headquarters. `` They are not going to enjoy it,'' she said.
