<HEAD>Communist Party Chief Criticizes Party's `Negligence'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Urbanek criticizing his Communist
Party for making mistakes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Karel </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> today said the party leadership had made mistakes marked by `` negligence and irresponsibility'' that led the organization into its worst crisis. Speaking to 1,500 delegates at a special party congress, <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> also admitted his own guilt as a member of the ruling Politburo in allowing hated hard-liners to remain in the party leadership. The party was expected to purge its ranks of many discredited party leaders during the two-day meeting. The Communists have been rocked by two shake-ups in the leadership to remove hard-liners and the loss of thousands of members since the country's peaceful pro-democracy movement began four weeks ago, changing the political orientation of the country. The congress, called to determine the party's future in the wake of a revolution that swept a government led by non-Communist into office, scrapped all its party statutes, which could pave the way for a comprehensive organizational reform. Party spokesman <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Hora </PERSON> told reporters the <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> also decided to divide the leadership duties between a general secretary and a party chairman. Former Premier <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON>, who resigned earlier this month after failing to reach agreement with the opposition on a new government, was thought to be a contender for one of the posts, according to congress observers who spoke on condition of anonymity. On Nov. 24, the party ousted hard-line leader <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and others responsible for the crackdown on the `` Prague Spring'' reforms of 1968, and <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> as party chief. The much despised <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> party boss, <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepan </PERSON>, was ousted two days later in a further leadership reshuffle that brought unknown Communists to the top. <PERSON> Stepan </PERSON>'s ouster was demanded by massive protest rallies. Both <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stepan </PERSON> were later expelled from the party for `` serious political mistakes.'' They had refuted assertions by a parliamentary commission that they were politically responsible for a Nov. 17 police crackdown on peaceful student demonstrators that ignited the ensuing democratic revolution. <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> said the `` party leadership manifested negligence and irresponsibility worthy of punishment.'' `` With self-criticism, I admit my part of the guilt in'' leaving <PERSON> Stepan </PERSON> on the Poliburo, <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> said, adding that the decision was `` an extraordinary, politically serious mistake.'' Outlining the crisis now faced by the party, <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> noted that it had lost 66,290 of its 1.7 million members in the last month. <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> also revealed that the party faces bankruptcy, disclosing that party dues were used to build recreation facilities for the top brass `` about which the rank-and-file only learned today.'' The speech confirmed the total disarray in which the party finds itself following the triumphs of the pro-democracy movement. The most recent victory came on Tuesday as the Communist-dominated <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> gave the new reform government a vote of confidence, and endorsed opposition leader <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> for president. `` There is no doubt that the congress delegates have the duty ... to take the party out of its deepest crisis ever,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Rude </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravo </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page editorial today. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, a former dissident who emobdies the democracy movement, said on the eve of the party congress that the party should become `` a modern political party which would participate as an equal among equals in the pluralistic system ...'' <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Prague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> delegates Tuesday night that new elections to the Politburo are not expected, but suggested it could be replaced by a 21-member `` political executive committee.'' Among the non-voting guests at the congress are former party members expelled after the Soviet invasion of 1968 that crushed the `` Prague Spring'' Communist-led reforms. There are also 40 delegates from the new reformist Communist Democratic Forum, a potential splinter group challenging <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON>'s leadership which submitted a seven point list of demands Earlier this week, the Democratic Forum spokesman, <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Prevratil </PERSON>, said `` the congress will show whether the movment can live within the party.'' The party was also likely to discuss the presidential elections. Communist Premier <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON>, who left for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> today and was therefore not attending the party congress, gave an unprecedented endorsement to <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>'s candidacy. The parliament's presidium voted late Tuesday to reconvene the house Dec. 29 at the presidential <LOCATION> Hradcany </LOCATION> castle to cast a public vote for president. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> is essentially the only candidate.
