<HEAD>Former Black Panther Leader Gets Probation in Bad-Check Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Black <PERSON> Panther </PERSON> <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> has been put on probation for a year for writing bad checks in a financially disastrous venture to sell ribs at a barbecue festival. <PERSON> Seale </PERSON>, 52, also was fined $ 1,000 Tuesday and ordered to serve 100 hours of community service. He pleaded guilty Nov. 20 to four misdemeanor counts after being charged with passing bad checks for more than $ 10,700 in ribs, lodging and other expenses for his booth at <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>'s National Rib Cook-Off in 1988. `` I had no intention whatsoever to defraud,'' he told Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Aurelius </PERSON>. `` I have a son in college ... I rent. I've been trying to take care of my family. I do all kinds of community service.'' <PERSON> Aurelius </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> has paid off his approximately $ 11,000 debt, which <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> said resulted from poor sales and higher-than-expected expenses. <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> was co-founder of the radical Black Panthers in the 1960s and was arrested with the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Seven for allegedly conspiring to incite the 1968 riots outside the Democratic National Convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> helps teach disadvantaged youngsters to rebuild abandoned houses in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where he is a community liaison for <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, his lawyer said.
