trial judge comments. ADDS two grafs with comments from Panamanian exile.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer for Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> said today the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader would die rather than surrender to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces sent to bring him to this country to face drug charges. Panamanian exiles here celebrated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attack. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted on federal drug charges in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> in 1988. Attorney <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Takiff </PERSON> said he talked with the general Monday evening. `` We discussed various things, including this very real possibility -LRB- of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military action -RRB-,'' the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> lawyer said in a telephone interview. The attorney said he had planned to fly to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> this evening to meet with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. This morning, he spoke with members of the general's staff who did n't know his whereabouts. `` He's a fighter,'' <PERSON> Takiff </PERSON> said. `` I feel unhappily secure in my belief that he will be killed, he will not be captured. Should that occur, the truth will never come out.'' <PERSON> Takiff </PERSON> questioned news accounts that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had declared war on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which he described as `` just some more propaganda that's come across again out of context.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeveler </PERSON>, assigned as the trial judge in the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> indictment, said today: `` If General <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is apprehended and brought here for trial, he would be given the same treatment as any other person accused of a crime _ no more, no less. All his rights will be protected.'' Also closely following events were members of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s Panamanian exile community, including <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, cousin of <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, who won the country's May election but was blocked by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from taking power. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> declared himself president shortly after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military action began. `` I can assure you 99.99 percent of all Panamanians are up. I know of at least five parties going on -LRB- in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> said in an early-morning telephone interview. He added that he had been in telephone contact with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` Many of the opposition's key people have taken refuge in safe places since we had reports way back from before the elections of May that the dignity brigades -LRB- armed citizens who support <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> -RRB- had lists of key opposition people to attack should something like this happen,'' he said. Convinced the military action would be a success, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> predicted many Panamanians living in this country would return to their homeland afterward. `` Exiles will probably return to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> once everything is back to normality,'' he said. `` We will probably see for the first time an emigration back to a country that has been liberated.'' Another Panamanian in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> said that if <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is captured, he will have to `` face all the things that he has done to the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people.'' `` I think he owes to the Panamanians many things and this is the first thing we have to face,'' said <PERSON> Aurelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barria </PERSON>, founder of the National Civic Crusade in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` We would like to find the truth of all the cases pending and try him in <LOCATION> Pa