<HEAD>If the Shoe Fits, Thief Wears It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A campus detective says he waited five years for the other shoe to drop _ make that shoes, dozens of shoes. That's what happened Tuesday when <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> police questioned a 33-year-old <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> man who admitted taking side trips to <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> for five years to steal shoes from students at campus libraries. Most of the shoes taken were men's penny loafers and deck shoes that students had kicked off while working. The man, identified as an assistant business professor at a private college, said he took shoes from libraries at UW-Madison, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University-Normal </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> at Champagne-Urbana, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> would not identify the man but said he had been convicted of theft in a missing shoe case at <LOCATION> Illinois-Normal </LOCATION> in July and is seeing a therapist. During six weeks in 1988, 12 pairs of shoes were stolen from the two UW-Madison libraries. Typically, a student would get up to get a drink of water and return to find his shoes gone. Police stepped up patrols in the libraries with no success. The break in the case came after shoes was stolen from a student Dec. 9, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said. The victim and a friend saw a man hanging around at the library with a pair of shoes sticking out of his backpack and questioned him, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said. The shoes were not the student's, but the man identified himself with an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> driver's license. When two more thefts were reported the same day, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> tracked down