<HEAD>Ex-Counselor Sues Salvation Army Claiming Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman who says she was forced to go outside her office to speak Spanish has filed a discrimination suit, charging her former employer's English-only policy insulted Hispanic employees. <PERSON> Ivette </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, a former probation counselor at the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, contended she was forced to resign in 1986 for failure to abide by a ban on speaking of Spanish during breaks. `` They said the only way I could speak Spanish during lunch was to go outside the building,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, 34, a native of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. `` I felt humiliated.'' Ms. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said the policy caused heart palpitations and emotional distress. She is seeking more than $ 10,000 in damages and reinstatement or reimbursement for lost wages in the suit filed Monday in federal court. Her bilingual ability helped her get the job in 1986 with the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which supervises people on probation for misdemeanors. Two months later, center director <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Hepperle </PERSON> ordered employees to stop speaking Spanish except when conversing with a Spanish-speaking client, she said. <PERSON> Hepperle </PERSON> said English-only rule was issued because some employees heard nothing but <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> and felt they were being talked about. Also, he had been told that some distasteful conversations were overheard by Spanish-speaking employees, he said. `` We're not here to discriminate against people. We're here to help people,'' he said.
