<HEAD>Pentagon Activates Media Pool for Panama Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> activated a news media pool that arrived in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> today alongside <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops dispatched by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The pool was developed after the controversy over secrecy surrounding the 1982 American military operation in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>. `` The purpose of the pool is to be there at the beginning of the operation,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition that he not be further identified. He said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> pools are usually disbanded after the first several days as other reporters arrive on the scene. Notifying and assembling the pool takes place under terms of secrecy that are unusual for the press. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> requires that pool members not tell others about their assignment. `` We ask them to tell their families that they have been called to work. That is not that unusual late at night for journalists. We ask them not to have their spouses drive them to <ORGANIZATION> Andrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, but to drive themselves or find some other way of getting there,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> source. The Pentagon pool in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is made up of journalists from the following news organizations: The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> Morning News. The initial writer's report was received at midmorning Wednesday, but news organizations were still waiting for photography from the pool well after noon. News executives receive short notice when a pool is being activated and assign the staff members who provide coverage. Their material is made available to other media organizations that do not take part. Participation in the pool is rotated several times a year. News executives notified that the pool has been activated are also sworn to secrecy. The first pool was formed in April 1985, and they have been assembled on average of twice a year since then, officials said. One pool accompanied <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships escorting oil tankers through the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in July 1987, but most times reporters receiving the midnight summons have watched military maneuvers. The most recent previous pool also went to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, in May 1989, a 12-member group that accompanied the first extra detachment of Marines sent there in Operation Nimrod Dancer. That pool was not kept secret, because President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced the operation earlier in the day.
