of a minute of silence. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, as host, declared to the conference that `` the Romanian regime of murderers will be unable to stay in power.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Vukovich </PERSON>, leader of the Austrian delegation, said all delegations condemned the events in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, but that the Soviet condemnation was restrained. The Soviets urged their Romanian allies to heed the human rights provisions of the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreements on European security and cooperation, he said. In <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership decided to `` stop concrete cooperation with the Romanian Communist Party for the time being.'' A statement from the party presidency held the Romanian party responsible `` for last weekend's tragic events and their consequences,'' the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> reported, and an invitation to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to send a delegation to the <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> party congress scheduled for January was withdrawn. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> gave a note to Romanian Ambassador Traian Pop that condemned `` the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrators.'' Legislators observed a minute of silence for the victims and voted to drape the parliament building in black. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s parliament condemned the crackdown and said the government in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> should `` draw the necessary conclusions'' from the events. There was no elaboration. The Foreign Ministry in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, where the beating of protesters started an uprising that ended the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> power monopoly in less than a month, protesting the use of force on demonstrators. Czechoslovak air controllers have urged an international boycott of Romanian plans. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Ionesco </PERSON>, the celebrated Romanian-born playwright, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> should help arrange the downfall of <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, the French newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Ionesco </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, said President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` alone can do something, because <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> is literally colonized by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' the newspaper reported.
