 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attack in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> early today left many civilians dead in the streets and touched off a fire that leveled a slum area around a Panamanian Defense Forces stronghold, witnesses said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in helicopters warned townspeople in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s capital of the impending attack, assuring them by loudspeaker that the soldiers `` did n't have a problem with the government,'' said one witness The witnesses spoke to reporters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> by telephone. `` They burned everything down,'' <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Backalt </PERSON> said in an interview from a <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> office near the Defense Forces headquarters where he fled with his wife and three children. `` I see plenty people dead in the street.'' He said the bodies _ he did not know how many _ were mainly members of the dignity battalions, civilian paramilitary groups loyal to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Speaking through an interpreter, <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, 32, who also took refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> office, said there were warnings in the night of the coming attack. `` Before they started to bomb, they warned -LRB- those in the area of <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> Defense Forces headquarters -RRB- to come out,'' he said. `` They were shouting down over the <ORGANIZATION> PA </ORGANIZATION> system saying ... they did n't have a problem with the government. At that point residents of the slum area surrounding the headquarters, a section of mostly wooden homes, headed into the streets, he said. `` They came out when they heard the announcement, and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soliders led them to a neighborhood church,'' <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said. He said the American soldiers moved in as he was heading to the church. During the attack a fire began, destroying the area, he said. Backalt, a self-employed stove repairman, said he was sleeping when he heard gunfire. He said his house caught fire, and he and his family went out into the street. None of his family was injured. As they walked the streets, he said, they saw a helicopter crash. He said he did n't know if it was an American or Panamanian helicopter. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiltshire </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> office, said <PERSON> Backalt </PERSON> was one of about 40 people near the office who were looking for assistance. He said it would be difficult to care for those displaced and injured in the attack. `` They want a place to stay because they are all burnt out. It's mounting up,'' he said <LOCATION> Wiltshire </LOCATION> said pro-Noriega forces were commandeering cars throughout the morning from people driving during the attack. `` They say, ` We're the police. We need your car,''' he said. His wife, <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON>, said they saw several families scurrying about with their possessions. `` They were carrying TVs and their belongings on their heads,'' she said. `` We're just about to get some meals cooked so we can service them.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> office is about two miles from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amador </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> base, and is near the headquarters of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Defense Forces. <LOCATION> Wiltshire </LOCATION>'s daughter, <PERSON> Avonnie </PERSON>, said she was awakened by the sound of shooting. `` I thought it was firecrackers. We realized after that it was a lot of gunfire,'' she said. `` We tried to stay away from the windows and doors.'' The <PERSON> Wiltshires </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> radio