<HEAD>Operations Superficially Similar, but Really Very Different</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Then as now, the invasion was launched in the pre-dawn hours. Then as now, the declared goal was to protect American citizens. But the similarities between the American landing on the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> on Oct. 25, 1983 _ the last time <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops were sent on an invasion _ and Wednesday's <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> are mostly superficial. Both were described as pre-emptive operations, but logistically and strategically they are largely different. The invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, spearheaded by 1,900 Marines and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION>, was undertaken with the stated purpose of protecting the lives of more than 600 American medical students from a Marxist government that had taken the island's government by force Oct. 19. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, too, said he had ordered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to protect the lives of Americans, this time an estimated 35,000, many of them soldiers. The presidential statements justifying the invasions was similar. Said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1983: `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' objectives are clear: to protect our own citizens, to facilitate the evacuation of those who want to leave, and to help in the restoration of democratic institutions in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>.'' Said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday: `` The <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people want democracy, peace, and the chance for a better life in dignity and freedom. The people of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> seek only to support them in pursuit of these noble goals.'' In <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces were under orders to capture <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the country's ruler who is under indictment in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug-trafficking charges. While both presidents said they were acting to restore democratic governments, the <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> operation had broader regional implications. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had grown increasingly concerned since 1981 about what he perceived as a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and Soviet military buildup on <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion was lent legitimacy by a request from six tiny eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nations for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> help to stop the military buildup, which they believed could endanger their democratic governments. Indeed, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> force was accompanied by 300 police officers and defense forces from four of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> neighbors. Although plans for both operations were long in the making _ the <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> invasion replicated a 1981 exercise _ the landing on <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> was much more of a surprise to the world. Many people did n't even know how to pronounce the name of the nutmeg-producing island and its new leader, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Coard </PERSON>, while years of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> clashes with the defiant and provocative <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> have become almost legend. The surprise six years ago was compounded by a lack of information about the operation in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> because of a complete <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> news blackout. Reporters were given access to the island only on the fifth day. The fighting in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was closely covered from the start by the resident news corps and, hours after the fighting began, by a pool of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reporters flown there by the Pentagon. In <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion was supported and prepared by some 13,000 troops already stationed at American bases there. In <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, there were no <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel on hand before the invasion. `` The logistics of getting there were much harder,'' said <PERSON> Langhorne </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Motley </PERSON>, who served as assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs at the time of the <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> invasion. The handkerchief-size <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> _ 8 by 18 miles with a population of less than 100,000 _ was a less complicated target than <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, with its 30,000 square miles and population of 2.3 million. `` <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is a much messier place to operate, with Americans scattered around the country'' and a professional, U.S.-trained military, <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> force _ which at the height of the invasion numbered about 7,000 _ encountered a military force of several thousand Soviet-armed troops, aided by about 600 armed Cubans there to construct a 9,500-foot airport runway that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said had no civilian use. Nineteen Americans were killed in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, several of them in accidents, as well as 24 <ORGANIZATION> Grenadans </ORGANIZATION>, most of them when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes mistakenly bombed a mental hospital. Also killed were 24 Cubans. The actual fighting for control of the island lasted about 36 hours, said <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>, a diplomat who headed the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> campaign to enlist public support for the <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> operation. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stayed about seven weeks to defend the interim government and clean up pockets of <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> resistance. `` But there was no real urban warfare, unlike <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>.
