<HEAD>Prosecutors Seek to Keep Family Jailed on Pot Smuggling Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION> and her two sons were behind bars today after being extradited from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> on charges of running a major marijuana smuggling ring. Less than 24 hours after their extradition, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilbrunn </PERSON> appeared in shackles Tuesday before a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate and were then jailed for a hearing Friday on whether to free them on bail before trial Feb. 13. `` The evidence we'll present will likely keep them detained,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> said. A 1987 indictment named them among 34 people charged with operating an 11-state ring that moved at least 250,000 pounds of marijuana _ one of the biggest such drug operations ever uncovered. They were arrested in May in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Before leaving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985, <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, 58, was president of the <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION> and the local chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of Jewish Women. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilbrunn </PERSON>, 35, was a commodities broker and columnist for a local business journal. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilbrunn </PERSON>, 38, lived with his wife and two children on a farm outside <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. `` This is a major milestone,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` Though we had felt confident that they would be home by the end of the year, it's good to see that process complete. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> and her staff waited for months while <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> processed hundreds of pages of documents, translated them into German and moved them through the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Of those indicted, 20 have been convicted, five are awaiting trial, five remain at large, and two have been acquitted, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Thar </PERSON> said. Charges against two were dismissed. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilbrunn </PERSON>, the alleged ringleader, faces possible life imprisonment on charges including conspiracy to import and distribute marijuana and running a continual criminal enterprise. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilbrunn </PERSON> faces up to 60 years in prison and <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> as much as 30. The indictment says the ring operated in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>.
