<SECOND>AM-Panama-UN,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says it Acted in Self-Defense in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said Wednesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> acted in self-defense when it sent its military forces to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to oust military leader Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power. <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON>, the ambassador of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, which called for an emergency <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meeting, retorted that `` the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no legal or ethical right to intervene in other countries' affairs.'' Speaking outside the council chambers, <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people `` have the right to self-determination; this action by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> violated the sovereignty of the Panamanian people.'' `` We want the council to call for an immediate withdrawal of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops,'' <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON> said, speaking in Spanish. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mission announced the Sandinista government had declared a national alert and mobilized troops against what President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said was <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s `` serious threat against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> ambassadors met individually in the morning and scheduled private consultations for the rest of the day; it was unclear whether a formal, public meeting would be held. <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had the right to intervene under Article 51 of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter, `` which provides for the use of armed force to defend a country, to defend our interests and our people, it's the so-called ` self-defense article.''' Panamanian soldiers shot and killed a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> officer at a roadblock on Saturday night. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s declaration last week that a `` state of war'' existed with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and `` the attacks on our citizens over the weekend are several of the things which the president has cited which required us to move in self-defense,'' <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said. Article 51 of the Charter permits the use of `` individual or collective self-defense if an armed attack occurs against a member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, until the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has taken measures necessary to maintain international peace and security.'' <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said he was talking with council members and favored more consultations before any public meeting is held. White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ordered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to seize <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and bring him to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for trial on drug trafficking charges. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> informed Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> of the military moves at 2 a.m. Wednesday, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief's spokesman, <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> is `` extremely concerned'' about the crisis, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> repeatedly has come before the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to complain of allegedly provocative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military maneuvers it said were intended to lay the groundwork for an invasion to topple the government. In August, <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> asked the council to send military observers to his country to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from goading confrontations as a pretext for armed intervention. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military observers, said <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>, `` will insure that the reality of the situation can not be hidden and it will be recorded in the annals of history as a crime.'' However, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> did not have any nation on the council introduce a resolution to send observers, a necessary step toward sending a mission. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> said in April and August that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is trying to provoke confrontations in order to keep control of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Under a 1977 treaty, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to turn over control of the canal to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> at the end of 1999.
