<FIRST>u i AM-Lithuania Bjt   12-20 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lithuania, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Communists Approve Break with National Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILNIUS, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lithuanian Communists voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to form an independent party, breaking <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s iron political unity for the first time in Soviet history. The Lithuanian party's congress of 1,038 delegates voted to declare themselves an `` equal partner,'' rather than a subordinate, of the Soviet Communist Party. Delegates at the <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> and Ballet Theater stood for a sustained ovation after the vote result was announced: 855 voted for independence, with 160 for retaining subordination to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party. Party chief <PERSON> Algirdas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON> congratulated the congress and expressed the `` hope and wish that our party will always be resolute, rejuvinated and ready for new battles.'' The party declared in a resolution it would `` maintain relations of equal partnership with the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, other progressive parties, public organizations and movements.'' `` The major goals of the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are an independent, democratic <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> state, implementation of the ideals of humanistic socialism, liberty and social justice, creation of adequate living conditions for the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> people and all the inhabitants of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>,'' the resolution said. The break runs counter to more than 80 years of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> practice and polcy. Since before the 1917 Russian Revolution, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> demanded a unified party covering the entire territory of the czarist empire. In 1921, the party formally outlawed the existence of factions. The vote came after two days of tough exchanges between the majority seeking a break with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and the minority, mostly ethnic <PERSON> Slavs </PERSON>, who opposed it. `` I believe that the formation of this kind of independent party leads practically to its annihilation,'' said <PERSON> Stefanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Serzhantovich </PERSON>, a tractor driver from rural <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> who is a congress delegate. But <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON> and other party leaders said such a split, including drafting a separate party program, was necessary for Lithuanian Communists to compete in Feb. 24 elections. The Communists, who supported a legislative move Dec. 7 to strike the leading role of the party from the Baltic republic's Constitution, will have to compete with the grassroots political movement <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION> and other newly formed parties in the local elections President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had appealed to the Lithuanians, most recently through party ideology chief <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, not to split, saying doing so would hurt his reform effort. <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, a conservative member of the ruling Politburo, said in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party's action `` is great trouble for the people and for the Communists.'' He said the Lithuanians `` just do not realize yet what grief will descend.'' Lithuanian party documents set a goal of restoring the republic's complete political independence, something <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has warned could upset the balance of a rapidly changing era. <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s action was the latest in a series of radical steps taken by Communist parties in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which have ended their monopoly on political power and allowed other parties to form. Writer <PERSON> Raimondas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasauskas </PERSON> told the delegates that an independent <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> was no danger to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, `` just like the existence of a peaceful <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> is not bad, just like the changes in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> do n't mean anything bad.'' `` It would be a disaster if the results of the voting would not meet the aspirations of the people,'' he said. <PERSON> Arvydas </PERSON> <PERSON> Matulionis </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, Philosophy and Law, told delegates 56 percent of local residents polled Nov. 30 approved of a separate <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He said 61 percent of the party members polled approved of the idea. Sajudis observers say local Communist Parties in other republics such as <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> could follow <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s example soon and present <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> with a splintered party when he convenes the 28th national party congress next fall. Ethnic Lithuanians make up about 80 percent of its 3.7 million people. Russians make up about 10 percent, and there are smaller populations of Poles and other ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
