<FIRST>u a PM-BusCrashTrial 3rdLd-Writethru a0718 12-20 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0718,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense in Bus Crash Says Vehicle's Manufacturer Was to Blame</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with deliberations under way. PICKS UP 8th
graf pvs, `Hildebrand and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury today began deliberating whether <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> is guilty of murder for each of the 27 people killed in a fiery 1987 collision between his pickup and a church bus. The jury received the case after <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s lawyers contended in closing arguments that the bus was unsafe and that the factory worker is not responsible for the deaths. Prosecutor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON> countered that bus safety was not the issue, adding, `` The apologies ... are too late. Now it's time to pay.'' <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> is charged with 27 counts of murder, 12 of assault, 42 of wanton endangerment and one of drunken-driving in what authorities have called the nation's deadliest alcohol-related traffic accident. Twenty-four youngsters and three adults from a church group died in the fire that engulfed the former school bus after <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s pickup rammed it on Interstate 71, five miles south of <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, on May 14, 1988 The chassis of the 1977 school bus was made by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s attorneys argued during his murder trial that the bus was unsafe because of a vulnerable gas tank and combustible interior materials `` Somebody should pay for it,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hildebrand </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s three attorneys. `` But <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> should not have to pay for something <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> did.'' <PERSON> Hildebrand </PERSON> and another defense attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON>, told the jury that <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> was intoxicated and was driving on the wrong side of the interstate. That caused the collision but not the fiery deaths, they said. `` <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> has the rest of his life, every waking minute, to remember this,'' <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said. No one `` can do anything to punish him worse.'' The prosecutor argued that <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s attorneys mounted an attack on the safety of the school bus out of desperation because no one could deny that <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> caused the crash. `` School buses do n't have anything to do with it,'' <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON> said. `` The elements of the alleged crime would be the same if <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> had collided with a motorcycle or a family car.'' The jury received instructions from Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> gave the jury two alternatives to the 27 murder charges _ second-degree manslaughter, punishable by five to 10 years in prison, and reckless homicide, punishable by one to five years. Murder is punishable by 20 years to life. To convict the 36-year-old <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> of murder, the jury would have to find that he had acted with `` extreme indifference to the value of human life,'' <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> told the panel. <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON> contended that <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s actions _ driving drunk and on the wrong side of a highway _ fit that description. The defense has claimed that <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> did not intentionally get drunk and that the former school bus, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sheller-Globe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was unsafe. Autopsies showed the fire, not the crash, killed the victims. <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> told jurors they would be sequestered, spending nights in a motel under sheriff's guard, until reaching a verdict. Once sequestered, jurors could not be released, even for Christmas, the prosecutor said.
