<HEAD>Court Hears Evidence in Lockerbie Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An appeals court Wednesday reviewed evidence against a Palestinian suspect in the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing amid heightened security for the first anniversary of the disaster. Another court in <LOCATION> Uppsala </LOCATION> will announce its verdict Thursday against the Palestinian, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>, on separate charges of murder and attempted murder for bombs directed against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Jewish targets in northern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1985 and 1986. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> faces a maximum life sentence, which in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> means 20 years or less. If convicted, he still could be extradited to stand trial in a foreign country on charges related to the Dec. 21, 1988, explosion over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, legal experts said. Scottish detectives questioned <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> in the Flight 103 case Tuesday, but the Swedish news agency <ORGANIZATION> TT </ORGANIZATION> reported that he refused to cooperate. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> was charged on one count of murder in the death of a passerby from a bomb outside the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orient </ORGANIZATION> airline office in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> in 1985. He was accused in other bombings in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. The 35-year-old former Egyptian army soldier and member of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Struggle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has lived in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> for six years. As friends and relatives of the 270 people killed on Flight 103 gathered in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> for the anniversary of the bombing, anti-terrorism experts in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> warned of possible at