<HEAD>Supreme Court Says Reporters Shouldn't Have To Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Journalists' confidential sources and information they gathered must be `` highly material and relevant,'' and unavailable from elsewhere, before reporters can be compelled to reveal them, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled. The 5-0 ruling released Wednesday, overturned contempt citations against two <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> reporters. In September, Circuit Judge <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> held in contempt reporters <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudok </PERSON> of The Evening Journal of <LOCATION> Martinsburg </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Natasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> of WXVA-FM in <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. They had refused to testify at a hearing about Circuit Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s decision to fire an employee `` In this case, the information sought to be obtained was tenuous at best to the main purpose of the hearing, which was to provide -LRB- the employee -RRB- a hearing on her discharge,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said. Eight news media groups, including The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, had filed a legal brief in support of the newspaper and radio station. `` The decision ... is really a victory for the people of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> because it allows reporters for all media to write the comments and viewpoints of the people who live in this state,'' said <PERSON> Page </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdette </PERSON>, editor of The Evening Journal. <PERSON> Burdette </PERSON> said he hopes the issue will prompt lawmakers to pass <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s first `` shield'' laws for reporters. Such legislation would help journalists protect news sources to whom they've promised anonymity in return for information. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said she was relieved. `` I'm just glad I get to eat turkey at Christmas and I do n't have to be in jail,'' she said. The opinion, written by Justice <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, said there could be cases when reporters' information is pertinent to a legal proceeding. In the case of <PERSON> Hudok </PERSON> and <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, however, First Amendment privilege should prevail, the opinion said. The case stemmed from <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON>'s decision to fire Magistrate Clerk <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Butner </PERSON> in June. The judge said she publicly injected herself into a criminal matter pending before magistrate court by talking to reporters. <PERSON> Steptoe </PERSON> had sought to force the reporters to testify about their conversations with <LOCATION> Butner </LOCATION>, who <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said is bound by judicial ethics to refrain from commenting on court matters.
