<HEAD>Britain Will Give Passports to Estimated 225,000 in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said Wednesday it will give special residence rights to an estimated 225,000 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> to prevent a crippling brain drain in the colony before it reverts to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1997. Right-wing legislators in the governing <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> threatened a parliamentary rebellion against what one called an appalling wave of immigration. The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> condemned the plan. Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> that a maximum of 50,000 key people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s public and private sector would be given full British citizenship, along with their families. He estimated the total at 225,000 people. Giving key people in government, business and the professions the right to live in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was essential to persuade them to remain in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and ensure that it passes `` successfully through the final eight years of British rule,'' he said. The confidence of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s 6 million residents was `` at a low ebb'' and the `` hemorrhage of talent'' was increasing, putting the competitiveness of its economy at risk, <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. This year, 42,000 people left and 55,000 are expected to leave next year. `` Many of those who are leaving would not do so if they could obtain the assurance of right of abode in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>,'' he said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> therefore decided to offer full British citizenship to a maximum 50,000 key people from many walks of life who will be selected on a `` points system,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. An estimated 1,500 families of Indian descent will be included. `` The decisive criteria will be the value of the individual's service to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and the extent to which people in their category of employment are emigrating,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said He said long service with British institutions and knowledge of English would be taken into account. About 3.25 million <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> Chinese have British passports, but no residence rights. <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said giving all of them the right to live in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would create `` unacceptable strains here'' while giving residency to just a few would n't solve <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s problem and might make it worse. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, the government welcomed the package though Governor Sir <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. Several legislators said they would have preferred full passports for all British nationals. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the package was not `` solely for the elite'' and would help create the stability the colony needed. But former <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Tebbit </PERSON>, the ringleader of an estimated 50 <ORGANIZATION> Tory </ORGANIZATION> rebels, icily told the foreign secretary he disagreed `` with almost everything you said.'' He demanded: `` Does the pledge that we have given for the last four general elections that there would be no further large scale immigration still stand or not?'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> retorted the aim was to persuade key people to stay in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> but even if many of them did emigrate, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would gain professional talent and expertise from one of the world's most successful societies. `` This is the last main chapter in the story of this country's empire I am rather keen, and I'm sure you are rather keen, that the last chapter should not end in a shabby way,'' he said. Conservative lawmaker <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> called the decision `` appalling'' and a guaranteed vote-loser in the next election, which must be held by June 1992. Fellow Conservative <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlow </PERSON> said many people would never forgive the government for opening the door to further immigration in overcrowded <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` They feel a deep resentment after a generation that imposed immigration into this country. I believe you will not be forgiven,'' he said. Labor lawmaker <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, the first black woman elected to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, accused <PERSON> Marlow </PERSON> of holding views similar to former <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON> Enoch </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> who opposed black immigration. `` Speaking in Mr <PERSON> Marlow </PERSON>'s words as an ` imposed immigrant' and an MP,'' she noted that `` people outside the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> have listened with mounting incredulity while elements in the Tory backbenches have out-bid each other with sub-Powellite rhetoric on this subject.'' She said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> must withdraw from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> `` with honor, and not in the shabby and shameful way some members are trying to create an issue of an imminent yellow peril.'' Labor's foreign affairs spokesman <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufman </PERSON> called the plan `` unreasonable, unworkable, invidious and divisive.'' Laborite <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaz </PERSON> said the plan represented `` one law for the rich and another for the poor.''
