<HEAD>Report: Army's Toughest Measures Failed to Reduce Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th, `Forty-three Israelis...,' to UPDATE
with 14 Palestinians wounded.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army's tough measures of house demolitions, deportations and school closures have failed to reduce protests by Palestinians and at times have inflamed the two-year uprising, according to a study published Wednesday. The study, part of an annual assessment of <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> military developments by <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jaffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, challenged often-stated army claims that strong reprisals served as a deterrent to unrest. Also on Wednesday, a military court sentenced three Palestinians to life in prison for an Oct. 30, 1988, firebomb attack on an Israeli bus that killed a mother and her three children as well as a soldier who tried to rescue them. Soldiers tried to attack the three defendants after the verdict and turned on reporters as they left the court. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> prisoner in the custody of the Shin Bet secret service was found dead Tuesday night in his cell. Arab reporters identified him as <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamel </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sheikh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and said he was taken for questioning Dec. 7. As a new step against the uprising, the army spokesman's office said the army would begin confiscating property of Palestinian parents who failed to cover the bail and fines of their children. In <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, a leaflet signed by the PLO-backed uprising leadership called for a general strike on Dec. 24 to mourn the deaths of the 631 Palestinians killed by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers and civilians in the revolt. Forty-three Israelis also have been slain, and 161 other Palestinians have been killed by fellow <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> as alleged collaborators with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, 14 Palestinians were shot and wounded in scattered stone-throwing clashes with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, Arab hospital officials said. Monsignor <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabbah </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> patriarch, called for peace in the Holy Land in his traditional Christmas message: `` Peace on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> is possible only when all people and all states concerned recognize the legitimate rights of all individuals and nations to freedom and self-determination.'' The study on the uprising in the <ORGANIZATION> Jaffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s annual Middle East Military Balance was based on army figures and conducted by <PERSON> Aryeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON>, a retired army brigadier general who served as military governor of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in 1976-78. `` What I discovered is there was no reduction in the number of incidents,'' <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> told a news conference. `` It means to my mind that -LRB- such measures -RRB- did n't have a serious effect on the strength of the intefadeh,'' uprising in Arabic. Since the uprising began in December 1987, army figures show 244 houses have been destroyed and 116 sealed. But <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> said they led to no decrease in violence as claimed by army commanders. `` We found no correlation whatsoever between the number of houses demolisehd and the number of violent incidents recorded, or the number of Israeli casualties, or even the number of petrol bombs thrown, in the following month,'' <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> wrote. In fact, his study showed, the number of incidents increased after the heaviest periods of house demolitions. For example, 24 houses were destroyed in November 1988, and incidents of stone throwing, barricade building and rioting rose by 1,195, or about 74 percent, to 2,790 in the following month. Deportation of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists has been considered the most severe measure against the uprising, but <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> said it proved impotent as a deterrent and actually inflamed the situation. `` There is a clear correlation between the number of residents deported ... and an ensuing increase in the number of violent incidents and Israeli casualties,'' he said. In April 1988, 16 Palestinians were deported, the largest number in a single month, but the number of violent incidents rose by 210, he said, adding there was a similar rise after 13 deportations in January 1989. In all, 60 Palestinians were deported in the past two years. <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> said closing schools initially appeared to have a restraining effect on violence in early 1988. But he said subsequent closures failed to have an effect and by early 1989 seemed to accelerate incidents. Universities have been closed since the start of the uprising. Elementary, junior and high schools were closed in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> for eights months in 1988 and throughout the first half of 1989. `` I do n't think it is possible to stop the intefadeh -LRB- uprising -RRB- by using these or other means,'' <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> told a news conference here, adding the only solution was a negotiated political settlement. <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> suggested mass deportations and demolitions might reduce violence but said such practice would not be possible because of legal and moral restaints.
