<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Wednesday branded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military attack in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> `` gunboat diplomacy'' and a violation of international law. It called for an immediate end to the operation. However, a Soviet official played down any impact the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action might have on improved superpower relations, and the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s rhetoric was far milder than its denunciations of the 1983 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> told a news briefing the sending of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, `` whatever its motivation, has provoked a feeling of serious concern in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action violated the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter and recognized rules of international relations and `` should be condemned by the international community.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said, `` must immediately stop its armed intervention in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' Millions of Soviets saw dramatic footage of the attack on the nightly TV newscast `` Vremya.'' Commentator <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Fyesunenko </PERSON>: `` Again, the world hears the loud voice of ` gunboat diplomacy' and understands perfectly well that the anger of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is caused not by the American concern about <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, but by the wish to disrupt the process of transferrence of the ownership rights of the -LRB- <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> -RRB- canal ... and to preserve the complex of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> military bases on the territory of this country,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said none of the arguments put forth by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to justify the military operation stands up to scrutiny. `` This action is an example of notorious ` gunboat diplomacy' which has been used for decades by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in an attempt to turn Latin American and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nations into its backyard,'' the official news agency said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the troops were sent to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lives and apprehend Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who stands accused by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of setting up a succession of puppet regimes while running a military empire that purportedly trafficked in Colombian cocaine. <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> dismissed the allegations of drug trafficking as a pretext to intervene in Panamanian affairs. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is steadfastly against international drug trafficking, he said, reflecting the Soviets' greater attention under leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to global problems that were once dismissed as symptoms of capitalist decay. `` We have something else here,'' <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> said. `` We are commenting on the intervention of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in a sovereign state. No matter what the motivation, this is something we are very concerned about.'' Despite Soviet concern, <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> indicated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action would not reverse the direction of improved Soviet-U.S. relations. `` We are now in a situation where an event in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> or in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is not perceived, is not evaluated, in terms of confrontation between East and West,'' the Soviet spokesman said. But, he said, `` I think both the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would stand to gain if a situation could be achieved where there is not interference in the affairs of others.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, however, said sending <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> did not involve just another regional conflict. `` It is a dangerous encroachment on the unsteady equilibrium that has been achieved in the world arena,'' it said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it said, `` has challenged the entire international community and is acting against universal human interests.'' Official Soviet reaction to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was markedly more restrained than when former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered the invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> in 1983. At that time, the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of carrying out `` a stinking show.'' It also said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was `` obsessed with the ideas of world domination.'' <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> said all countries would benefit from policies of non-interference, which the Soviet leadership under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has repeatedly professed to be its policy. `` All states would stand to gain when all peoples of all countries decide their own destinies,'' <PERSON> Perfiliev </PERSON> said.
