<HEAD>Producer Recalling Cajun Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> processor is voluntarily recalling about 1,000 pounds of a frozen pork and rice product because it might be contaminated with a food-poisoning organism, Listeria monocytogenes, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Bodin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, sells the product through small distributors in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. It is sold frozen in vacuum-sealed plastic packages with the name `` Boo <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Boudin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Link </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Traditional Cajun Pudding'' on the label, and `` Est. 8214'' printed inside the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> inspection seal on the label. A <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the product is cooked pork and rice wrapped in a sausage casing, or link. Each 10-ounce package sold in grocery stores contains two links and is shipped 12 per carton. Ten-pound bulk packages sold to restaurants and delicatessens contain approximately 30 links. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, head of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said consumers `` should not unwrap or taste the product'' and should return it to where it was purchased. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> confirmed the presence of Listeria monocytogenes while investigating a case of listeriosis, the disease caused by the organism. Listeriosis was described as `` a rare but potentially serious'' disease. Most vulnerable are those with weakened immune systems, including infants, the elderly and the chronically ill. Symptoms in adults include the sudden onset of flu-like symptoms such as fever, chills, headache, backache, and sometimes abdominal pain and diarrhea. In newborns, symptoms include respiratory distress, refusal to drink and vomiting. Consumers with question about the recall may phone the toll-free <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> meat and poultry hotline at 1-800-535-4555 between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m. EST, Monday through Friday. Callers in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, metropolitan area may call 447-3333.
