<HEAD>Moscow, Prague to Examine Soviet Troop Presence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed Wednesday to begin reviewing the presence of 80,000 Soviet troops stationed here since the `` <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Spring'' reforms were crushed in 1968. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> and Premier <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> told reporters after returning from a one-day visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that a joint commission will be set up in the first half of January. The commission, composed of civilian and military experts, also will re-examine the political and historical events that led up to the Soviet invasion and its consequences, <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> said at an airport news conference. <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON>, who has said he hopes an agreement can be reached soon on the withdrawal of Soviet troops, told reporters the commission would `` deal with all aspects of the Soviet military presence'' in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> was asked if there would soon be a timetable for a pullout of the troops, which have been stationed in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> on a `` temporary'' basis for 21 years. `` I do n't know, but I think we will have results in this area that will satisfy the nation,'' <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> replied without elaboration. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> announced that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had agreed to negotiate its troop presence in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> and his Soviet counterpart, <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, agreed to begin the talks in the first two weeks of next month. The dispatch did not say the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would be negotiating withdrawal of its troops, but the Czechoslovak state news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> has said the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc country would begin preliminary negotiations for the pullout of Soviet troops. <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> said he met with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> for more than an hour Wednesday. <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> met with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> said he left <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with the feeling that there was `` great understanding for this question.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, who led the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Spring movement crushed by the Soviet-led <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invasion in August 1968, signed the initial document allowing the troops' presence after tense negotiations in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, where he was flown right after the invasion. Since the ouster of hard-line communist leaders the last month, the new Czechoslovak leadership has said the agreement was invalid because it was signed under duress. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> apologized for its hard-line policies of the past and for abusing its opponents after the 1968 crackdown. Earlier this month, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> condemned the invasion as a mistake. Under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has vowed not to interfere in the affairs of its <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact allies. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> also have apologized for their roles in the invasion. <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> sai before the visit that any troop withdrawals must run parallel with <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> talks on conventional weapons reductions under way in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, where a preliminary accord is expected next year. Faced with a peaceful revolution, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s hard-line President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> resigned Dec. 10 after swearing in the new government dominated by non-communists. Other hard-line leaders associated with the crackdown that followed the invasion have been ousted from power and purged from the party.
