<SECOND>AM-Poland,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Wins First Bill in Economic Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament approved a farm bill with only one dissenting vote Wednesday, indicating it will accept the entire government plan to transform <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s centralized economy into a market-oriented system. The vote of 284-1 followed more than two days of sharp debate, much of it critical of the government's agricultural policies, and represented overall support for reform beyond party lines. Industry Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Syryjczyk </PERSON> and the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Osiatynski </PERSON>, said they felt the entire package would be approved. A finance official said a letter of intent on an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> agreement would be signed with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> soon. The Soviet bloc's first non-Communist government, led by Solidarity, is pushing economic reform in an effort to conquer annual inflation of 900 percent a burdensome $ 39 billion foreign debt and qualify for desperately needed Western economic aid. Officials acknowledge the program, which takes controls off prices, ends most subsidies and limits wage increases and will be painful in the beginning. It is expected to cause a 20 percent drop in real incomes and put 400,000 people out of work in a nation unaccustomed to unemployment. Before Wednesday's vote, <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, the Solidarity leader in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said in urging support for the farm resolution: `` We are convinced that Polish farmers ... will be able to understand the interests of the state.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> and the architect of economic reform, Deputy Premier <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Balcerowicz </PERSON>, sat side by side in the chamber as the vote was taken. By Wednesday, three days after <PERSON> Balcerowicz </PERSON> presented the economic plan to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, the government appeared increasingly confident of passage. <PERSON> Osiatynski </PERSON>, head the planning office, said: `` I think it will be voted in before the first of January. The difficulties will start only once it is voted in and once we start carrying it out.'' <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawicki </PERSON>, deputy finance minister, said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> would sign a letter of intent with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> `` within the upcoming few days.'' After the letter is signed, <PERSON> Sawicki </PERSON> said, he expects the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> to announce preliminary acceptance of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s economic reform program. He said that would allow <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to get a $ 215 million bridge loan from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Settlements </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and release a $ 1 billion loan pledged by a group of Western countries, led by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to support turning the zloty into a convertible currency. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> is expected to ratify the agreement at the end of January or early February, <PERSON> Sawicki </PERSON> said. In it, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> agrees to continue a strict regimen of reform in exchange for a $ 700 million line of credit from the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>. Certification by the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> would open the way to money from other Western lenders, including a <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loan of $ 300 million, and rescheduling of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s $ 40 billion hard-currency debt.
