<HEAD>Former Southern Command Chief Says Military Attack `Well-Planned'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, said Wednesday that the military strike against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was `` well-planned and well-executed'' even though he has long opposed the use of force there. Retired Gen. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, who left the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> on Sept. 30, also said the operation would be judged `` a disaster, an absolute catastrophe'' if Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> returns to power. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> had opposed military intervention in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, advocating diplomatic and other peaceful options to dislodge <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The Panamanian leader has been indicted on drug charges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Various <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administrations failed to deal successfully with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, ultimately pushing President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> into a corner where he could do nothing except send in the military, <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had no other options. It had reached a point where an American was killed,'' he said. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for the military strike to protect the lives of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> and ensure freedom of movement in the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Although he did not have inside knowledge of the military operation, <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said it appeared from news reports that it was handled professionally and competently. `` The military operation looked well-planned and well-executed,'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said, adding, however, that it apparently took longer than expected. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> described <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as `` a clever, clever guy.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operation wo n't be considered successful unless <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is either captured or driven from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and never returns, <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said. He said he did not think <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would call off the operation until it was certain that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> could never return to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.
