<HEAD>Slain Federal Judge Eulogized Under Tight Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mail Bombs-Jacksonville, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XBM3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN BROOK, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bomb-sniffing dogs and squadrons of police provided tight security Wednesday as a crowd of mourners paid their respects to a federal appeals judge killed by the first in a series of mail bombs. <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> was filled to overflowing with more than 700 people who were asked to put aside their anger over the slaying long enough to remember the contributions of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>. Dogs searched the church before the service, and dozens of officers kept watch during the 35-minute program of scripture, hymns and a eulogy. <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>, a member of the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was killed instantly last Saturday when the bomb exploded in his home, propelling nails into his lower abdomen. His wife, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, was injured in the bombing and remained hospitalized Wednesday. A similar bomb two days later killed a civil rights lawyer in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, City Alderman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. A package bomb was found in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> courthouse including the 11th Circuit on Monday and a fourth mailed bomb was removed Tuesday from the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. All four targets can be linked to school desegregation efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, leading investigators to speculate that a white racist group may be responsible Four anonymous letters mailed in August to declare war on various federal appeals courts are being examined for clues to the bombings, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The bombs and threats has prompted the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> to boost security at its offices, executive director <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said Wednesday at the organization's national headquarters in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. Hooks said he's convinced the bombs were the work of white supremacists who feel threatened by recent victories for blacks in courtrooms and at the polls. `` I think it's the work of white supremacists, without any question. I think it reveals the derangement, demented, criminally stupid minds,'' he said. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> are denying any involvement. `` There ai n't nobody in any white supremacist group got sense enough to make a bomb,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carver </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> grand dragon of the Invisible Empire Knights of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm hoping if it's one of those big drug dealers, maybe they'll take credit for it and get the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> off our backs. <PERSON> Carver </PERSON> was one of several defendants who had appealed a $ 950,000 jury verdict against two Klan groups for pelting civil rights marchers with rocks and bottles in <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The 11th Circuit refused in October to rehear the defendants' appeal. At <ORGANIZATION> Vance </ORGANIZATION>'s service, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulford </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, a close friend of <LOCATION> Vance </LOCATION>, delivered the eulogy, asking the mourners to `` put aside our outrage for awhile'' to honor <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>. `` The assassins were cheated if they thought that <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> was afraid to die,'' <PERSON> Fulford </PERSON> said. He described the 58-year-old <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> as a strong believer in the law and a man `` who stood up for the underdog and the oppressed.'' `` No wonder his assassins could not stand such a man in their presence.'' Friends of the <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> family said his remains have been cremated and his ashes will be placed in the church. Because of the rash of bombs, and the attendance of public officials, the church, south of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, was surrounded by police barriers and cordoned off with yellow tape. Among those who attended the service were Sessions, Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the justice who oversees the operations of the 11th Circuit, which handles appeals from <LOCATION> Floria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
