<HEAD>Smithsonian Says 11 Scientists, Technicians Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that 11 scientists and technicians associated with the its <ORGANIZATION> Tropical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> are missing and are believed to have been abducted. `` These people have disappeared, and we're very concerned,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>. `` We have every reason to believe they were taken hostage.'' Ms. <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said the scientists, five Americans, five Panamanians and one Venezuelan, were working at a marine research facility on the Sanblas chain of islands off the Panamanian coast in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> when they were abducted by armed troops. A <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> employee on the island called the research institute's director in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at midmorning by radio telephone to warn that the troops were approaching in a boat. A couple of hours later, a technician on the island called briefly to say they were being transferred to the mainland and taken by truck to an unknown destination. Ms. <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said most of the 190 other <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> employees and visiting scientists in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> had been accounted for.
