<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DRESDEN, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> recommended Wednesday that <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> become stronger economically before considering reunion with its rich and powerful neighbor. At the end of an emotional visit to the East, he also discounted fears of a `` Fourth Reich,'' an increasingly used term that raises the specter of <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, who arrived in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> for a three-day official visit hours after <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> returned to the West, cautioned against changing borders in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` For the whole of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, it would not be good _ indeed it would be very dangerous _ to reopen the issue of the existing borders,'' he said. Before returning to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said `` the economic potential of the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Democratic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> must be strengthened'' before reunification became a possibility. He said he expected a treaty expanding relations to be completed before <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s first free elections, scheduled for May 6. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, in an interview with East German TV before leaving <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, said relations between the two German states have `` very special characteristics.'' He was the first head of state or government of the three western World War II Allies to visit <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. Aides said his trip should not be viewed as recognition of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> as the East German capital, which the Western Allies reject. The <LOCATION> Unite