rly.'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> told reporters inter-German issues that could be discussed soon included improving traffic connections and solving joint telecommunications and pollution problems. `` We will have to work intensively'' on a common German currency, he said, and acknowledged that as `` one of the most difficult questions.'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said the aim of a common currency was to allow West Germans to buy goods in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> restricts such purchases because state subsidies make many goods much cheaper than in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and shortages are feared. In a sign of the rapidly increasing economic links, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> announced Wednesday the first joint venture with a West German firm had been signed. A compact disc manufacturing plant is to be built by the <PERSON> Pilz </PERSON> company, based outside <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, and the East German state conglomerate Robotron. In <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, a working group of both nations on promoting tourism held its first meeting. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will support reform in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and `` not only talk, but act.'' He pledged, however, to avoid `` destabilization,'' an apparent reference to the power vacuum created by the collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> control over the past two months. Addressing the concerns of neighboring countries, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said: `` Fears based in the past are understandable, but there is nothing to be feared from the future. It's absurd to talk about a Fourth Reich.''
