participate for fear of being isolated within their groups. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had no immediate comment on the conference, said spokesman <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shubb </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> was seen as the most reluctant Arab participant because of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s military intervention on behalf of the government of <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> against Libyan-backed rebels, as well as the French decision to renew the ban on shipment of French-made arms to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The government of Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> decided to participate `` only at the urgent request of its Arab brothers,'' <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> JANA </ORGANIZATION> news agency said The first steps to creating an `` Arab-European dialogue'' were taken in 1973 when the oil crisis had brought the <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states to the high point of their power. The earlier attempt collapsed largely because of political problems, including accusations of terrorism against <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. For the current conference, the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> government has reoriented the agenda more toward economic matters. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is concentrating on a selected list of specific to avoid getting bogged down in political subjects, such as the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to challenge the export of citrus fruit from the Israeli-occupied territories to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> The agenda includes such items as agreements on trade in petrochemicals, the exchange of consulting engineers, an Arab-European financial convention, European aid to the North African railroad network and preparatory work for the proposed fixed link _ by tunnel or bridge _ across the Strait of <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>.
