<HEAD>Allegations That Dogs Were Buried Alive at Landfill</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SHERA GROSS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A regional humane society is investigating charges that a county dog pound has been burying alive unwanted dogs and cats, officials said Wednesday. A number of people reported seeing animals squirming in the back of a pickup that was taking animals to a landfill for burial. However, <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials are denying that the animals, which were supposed to have been killed by carbon monoxide poisoning, were alive when buried. <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who works at the landfill office, said she was working Tuesday when a truck filled with animals in plastic bags from the <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Dog Pound pulled up. `` I saw movement in the back of the truck,'' Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` At first I thought it was the wind, but then I noticed it made a teepee effect, like a paw reaching up.'' The driver, who was outside the truck to obtain papers from Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s office, `` swatted the bag with the back of his hand,'' Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` Then he pulled up two other trash bags as if he was trying to cover it up.'' <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Cockrum </PERSON> said the animals were checked before they left the pound in <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION>. The board oversees the pound. `` When we destroyed animals yesterday -LRB- Tuesday -RRB- morning we had a veterinarian to check each and every animal and he assured us that each one was dead before they left the pound,'' <PERSON> Cockrum </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> of <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said he and his two sons examined four dogs they found at the landfill. `` One of them my boy picked up and it gave out a pitiful whine and then it went limp in his arms,'' he said Wednesday. The other three animals were warm and limp and appeared to have been dead only minutes, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cockrum </PERSON> called the reports by Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> hearsay. About 45 animals are destroyed every two weeks at the pound. They are put in steel boxes linked to the exhaust pipe of a vehicle and are asphyxiated with carbon monoxide, <PERSON> Cockrum </PERSON> said. The carcasses are dumped at the landfill within two hours of death, including the 45-minute ride from <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Carbondale </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cockrum </PERSON> said 28 animals were killed Tuesday, including eight or nine cats. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said he found another dog barely alive in October and asked the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> to perform an autopsy on the dog. Dr. D.K. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> confirmed that he performed the procedure at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Centralia </LOCATION>. The autopsy found that the dog had been alive about three hours after it was buried, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. It also found that the animal's organs were severely burned from inhaling carbon monoxide, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> <PERSON> Dantzler </PERSON>, regional director for the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said asphyxiation with carbon monoxide is an `` extremely painful'' method of euthanasia. The most humane and least painful method is lethal injection of barbiturates, he said. <PERSON> Dantzler </PERSON> said his offers to the county for help in finding a more humane euthansia system were ignored. The society plans to investigate the matter further, <PERSON> Dantzler </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home in South Bend, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.
