<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> adminstration argued Wednesday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was legal under both domestic and international law but some lawyers who have tried war-powers cases disagreed. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> cited Article 51 of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Charter that gives nations the right to act in self-defense and a similar provision of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> treaty as the legal basis for the invasion. Article 21 of the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> treaty gives the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the right to protect its citizens, installations and institutions, the secretary said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> also cited the terms of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal Treaty that give the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the right to exercise force to protect the canal to keep it operating. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> advised President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> about the legality of the operation before it was launched, said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> `` believes there is a legal basis for this action being taken under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. `` It is my understanding there is clearly legal authority under both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law and international law.'' But two attorneys for the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, a liberal New York-based civil liberties group, disagree. ` I'd say it's clearly illegal under the <ORGANIZATION> UN </ORGANIZATION> Charter and the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> charter,'' said attorney <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON>, who is also a law professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does n't have the right to unilaterally decide to overthrow another governent by the use of force,'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said. `` Nothing that the president said today or the secretary of state said would give the the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> such a right.'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must show it is acting in self-defense for the invasion to be legal under the <ORGANIZATION> UN </ORGANIZATION> Charter and the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> treaty. `` I do n't think that can be based on some speculated threat that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens might be endangered,'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> had cited an intelligence report that Panamanian Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noreiga </PERSON> was poised to attack Americans. `` If <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens might be endangered, the obvious thing to do is to protect them and evacuate them not overthrow the government,'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said. Both <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, another attorney for the center, said the invasion also violated the war-powers provision of the Constitution, which requires congressional approval of the deployment of troops in this fashion. `` I think the intent of the framers of the Constitution is clear, if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is going to offensively use military force abroad it must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and not by four leaders in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Lobel </PERSON> said. `` As a purely technical constitutional matter, the president does not have the authority to do what he did,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` As a matter of legal and political reality, if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't try to stop him, I think it's unlikely the courts would.'' <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Koh </PERSON> voiced caution about the invasion, saying `` the rationale of protecting the securityof the canal must be limited to making sure there is no damage to the canal or some impairment of the security of the canal.'' `` It ca n't be an all-purpose justification of wide-ranging actions to restructure the government,'' <PERSON> Koh </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Koh </PERSON> also expressed skepticism about justifying the invasion as an effort to arrest <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` As a matter of international law, there is a danger in converting political action into so-called crime fighting action.''
