comment from white Council member. Willye in 9th graf is correct</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Civil rights leaders said Wednesday they've made progress in this northeast <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> city, but the mailing of a bomb to <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> headquarters recalls recent racial tensions that had begun to fade. The bomb disarmed here Tuesday was similar to devices which killed a federal appeals court judge and a <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, civil rights leader. Bombs mailed to the 11th <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and to the <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People were disarmed without causing any damage or injuries. Possible links to <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> school desegregation efforts have been identified in all four cases, leading to theories that a racist group may be responsible. Racial tensions were heightened here in September when three black City Council members were ordered arrested after they walked out of a meeting to protest lack of funding for predominantly black areas in the city budget. One of them, attorney <PERSON> Deitra </PERSON> <PERSON> Micks </PERSON>, was arrested in a City Hall women's room and hauled back to the council meeting in handcuffs. The arrests were ordered by <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Tillie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, who is white, so the council would have a quorum. `` And all of a sudden this happened, so it just brings up this whole issue of race again,'' the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, a black minister, said Wednesday. `` <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> is sitting on a racial powder keg, I'm sorry to report.'' Black leaders said they were angry about Tuesday's discovery of the bomb, but it will not deter them from their work. `` We will go on with our business as usual. We will not let this incident stop us from doing the job we have set out to do,'' said <PERSON> Willye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, the local president of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. She received the explosive package Monday, but did n't have time to open it then. She had a more optimistic view of racial tension in the city. `` We've come a long way in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, but we have a long way to go,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, who is white, said he believes tensions have eased since the walkout. `` But there are elements on both sides who can point to certain events and say improvements are superficial,'' said <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>. <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Calvary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, said the organization has received criticism from both whites and blacks for its positions. `` On one hand we have threats from whites, perhaps racists, who want to destroy us because of positions of ideology ... and on the other hand, to try to stop drugs we have threats from blacks who happened to be drug dealers who want to blow us away,'' <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that all four bombs had <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> postmarks or return addresses. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinshaw </PERSON>, in charge of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> office, said the first parcel bomb, addressed to federal Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>, was mailed last Thursday from <LOCATION> Newnan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, to <