<HEAD>Bush Says Military Strike `Decapitates' Noriega From Dictatorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Wednesday he ordered the military strike in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to seize <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and end `` reckless threats and attacks'' against Americans. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> eluded capture and the administration put a $ 1 million bounty on his head. Even though <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> dropped out of sight, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said, `` As a practical matter, we have decapitated him from the dictatorship.'' The White House announced a $ 1 million reward for information leading to his capture. In addition, Panamanians were offered $ 150 for each firearm they surrendered. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials declared the operation in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> a military success, saying <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s forces mostly had fled or were fleeing though some fighting continued. Reaction from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, both Democratic and Republican, was mostly favorable. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, hoping to break a nearly two-year stalemate with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, dispatched 9,500 soldiers and Marines to back up the 13,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops already in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> for a 1 a.m. assault against army bases and the general's headquarters. In a televised address from the Oval Office, a somber <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the nation, `` I took this action only after reaching the conclusion that every other avenue was closed and the lives of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens were in grave danger.'' In the fighting _ codenamed `` Operation Just Cause'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> _ 15 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel were killed, many more were wounded and one was missing. In addition, a woman dependent was killed, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. Four helicopters crashed, believed to have been brought down by gunfire. Noting the loss of American lives, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` No president takes such action lightly.'' Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> deputy chief of staff, said, `` One dead American is too many, but thank God the numbers do n't appear too high right now.'' He said, `` It looks like the organized resistance is a thing of the past.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, up much of the night, monitored the fighting in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. He took a break Wednesday evening to attend a White House Christmas party. Some Americans were reported taken hostage in the <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Late in the day, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines arrived at the site and escorted many Americans out of the building. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> called <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> `` a crafty devil'' and said he had not been spotted Wednesday. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces had observed <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> several times on Tuesday. `` We thought we had a pretty good idea of where he was last night. We went there and he was n't there.'' `` He has gone to ground,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. Even so, he expressed confidence <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would be located, saying `` we have every spigot turned on'' to find him. He said there was no indication <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had left <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The general said `` much of the PDF -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is fleeing in the face of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military units.'' He added, `` We have a concern that they have gone off into the jungle. There is every chance that we will go off after them.'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said he expected the canal to reopen Thursday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would withdraw its force as soon as possible. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said he could not speculate how long <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops would remain in action. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was roundly criticized when he kept <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces on the sidelines during an unsuccessful coup attempt against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on Oct. 3. In contrast, congressional leaders generally supported the president's decision to use force. `` When there is the engagement of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the field, it behooves all of us to give that support,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. `` It was made necessary by the reckless actions of Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>. But Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s action `` a trigger-happy act of gunboat diplomacy'' which violates the Constitution And, Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should not have acted without the support and aid of other Central American nations. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, the director of national drug control policy, said of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, `` I think we can safely conclude that this ends his career as a drug trafficker. He's not running drugs. He's not running <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> He's just running. And that's good.''
