<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Youngsters calling <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION> over the past week may have been thinking of his sleigh and eight tiny reindeer, but they got the people who keep 530-mph, four-engine military radar reconnaissance jets in the air. And most of them will never know they got the wrong number. The children got connected to technicians at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s support center for specially equipped military aircraft. `` This was quite a surprise when it started out,'' said <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON>, developer with the Airborne Warning and Control System, or AWACS, fleet support system. `` But after the first several calls we figured out what had happened, and just started answering phones as if this was Santa's workshops. Hundreds of children got their lines crossed because of transposed numbers in a telephone listing in a national magazine, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Pulham </PERSON> said Wednesday. The aerospace branch of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> specializes in missiles, spacecraft and spy airplanes _ for some, the ultimate toys. He said the calls began about Dec. 13 and were winding down by the middle of this week, after calls for <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> were redirected. The first youngsters might have been greeted with, `` Hi. This is AWACS Fleet Support Central. Can I help you?'' <PERSON> Pulham </PERSON> said. But the engineers lightened up and played along. `` They were putting on their bonnets, and would play <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> whenever the children would call, but they would give technical information when customers called,'' he said. The normal phone calls to the center are for technical assistance provided for those who fly, service and repair the AWACS aircr