ban on reporters accompanying the initial phases of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attack in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> in 1982. This group's TV gear included a portable satellite ground station. But even though reporters were flown around the battle areas in helicopters, it appeared late Wednesday afternoon that unexplained snags had developed and there'd be no pool pictures from the transmitter, <PERSON> DeCesare </PERSON> said. `` They have the capacity to feed -LRB- video reports -RRB-,'' he said. `` However, we still have yet to receive anything.'' He and his <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> counterparts were relieved when, at about 35 minutes before their networks' first evening newscasts, the pool's videotape footage began coming in from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Some shots were taken over a the shoulder of a helicopter door gunner.
