<HEAD>Tennessee Secretary of State Dies From Dec. 12 Gunshot Wound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> Gentry </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>, who shot himself in the head last week as a corruption probe tightened around his office, died Wednesday after doctors declared him brain-dead. <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>, who was not implicated personally in the investigation, had been in a coma since shooting himself once with a .38 - caliber revolver at his home Dec. His condition worsened Tuesday night as tests showed a restricted blood flow to the brain. Final tests showed little blood flow, and doctors decided Wednesday to remove him from life-support systems, said Dr. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, an associate vice chancellor at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` He essentially was found to have no brain function,'' <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said. `` It was comparable to an extensive or massive stroke.'' <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>, 57, never regained consciousness after the shooting. He had remained in critical condition and was treated with intravenous injections of a drug designed to remove fluids from the brain and reduce swelling. Gov. <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> McWherter </PERSON> issued a statement of condolence to <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>'s family, who were at the hospital when he died at 1:19 p.m. `` This is a sad and unfortunate time for his wife, Terrijean, and their children, <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> McWherter </PERSON> said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> was appointed by <PERSON> McWherter </PERSON> on Tuesday to fill <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>'s role until the Jan. 9 convening of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, which can appoint a successor. Controversy, much of it growing out of his passionate devotion to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, followed <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> during most of his 18 years in state government. He was once known as `` The Godfather'' on Capitol Hill because of his absolute, partisan control over legislation in the dual roles of chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> and the House Calendar Committee. As secretary of state, he was in charge of regulating bingo and spending by lobbyists and political campaigns, all of which were involved in the federal-state investigation into public corruption. He testified in September and November 1989 before federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> investigating bingo corruption in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. He said he was told by federal agents that he was not a target of the investigation. As a result of the probe one former <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> aide, former chief bingo inspector W.D. `` Donnie'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, has gone to federal prison in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>; his longtime aide, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, has been named an unindicted co-conspirator and given immunity from prosecution. Ms. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> kept the books on a campaign fund started by <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> and two other constitutional officers on behalf of Democratic candidates for the Legislature. She admitted taking thousands of dollars from the fund, and a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> has subpoenaed records from it. The secretary of state's office had regulated charitable bingo since it was legalized for charity fund-raising in 1971. It did not become controversial, however, until 1979, when the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> outlawed bingo on the final day of the session. After protracted negotiations between the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the game was made legal again in 1980 and the Office of Charitable Solicitations was put in charge. Every year thereafter, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> amended the bingo law in an effort to weed out professional gambling. In October 1987, <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> revoked the bingo license for a <ORGANIZATION> Kingsport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AmVets </ORGANIZATION> post on grounds the group gave little of its profits to charity. The case was appealed up to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which ruled bingo an unconstitutional lottery in February 1989.
