<HEAD>Financial Markets Have Muted Reaction to Panama Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `On Wall ..., to CORRECT that advancing stocks
outnumbered declining issues; picks up 6th graf: `Analysts said ...; a
version also moving on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Only a few blips registered on financial markets Wednesday as investors took the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in stride. The dollar, oil and many stocks moved higher on the news of the surprise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military operation, but prices later receded amid the usual concerns about interest rates and the economy. `` The initial reaction is one of a non-event,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON>, a stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It might have an impact if it becomes a prolonged situation.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ordered troops into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> following several days of tension triggered by the weekend shooting death of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officer by defense forces controlled by Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average, a key barometer of financial reaction to outside events, closed down 7.68 points to the 2,687.93, following an initial rise. Stocks advancing in price narrowly outnumbered declining issues on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> confrontation's economic effects were unclear, but investors remain worried about the health of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy in general. Most experts did not view the Panamanian situation as a reason for making big changes in their investment strategies. `` We've been involved in limited engagements before. This looks like a military engagement that will be over shortly,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, a vice president for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Some analysts said they looked upon the assault as generally positive because it showed the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration meant business. `` I think people are encouraged by the forceful action by our government,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, a technical analyst with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` But there's a lot of anxieties on Wall Steet ... worries about the real estate market and a looming recession.'' In another sign that the economy was dominating investor thinking, some <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond prices moved slightly higher in late <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> signaled it might lower interest rates. The prospect of lower rates on government issues often spurs demand for existing bonds, pushing prices higher. Speculation about lower rates also helped depress the dollar in foreign exchange trading. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency initially rallied on the news of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> action because in times of international tension investors buy dollars and precious metals as safe havens for their money. The dollar closed sharply higher in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, but was mixed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gabriele </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, a trader with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, said the dollar still had room to rise because of the uncertainty in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` There are still a lot of question marks,'' she said. `` <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> still has a lot of support in his country ... I would n't rule him out entirely.'' Gold prices were not affected significantly by the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> news but managed to finish slightly higher in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading. The oil futures market initially rallied, but prices fell back later in the day. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the leading grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, was down 7 cents to settle at $ 21.21 per 42-gallon barrel. The January home heating oil contract, supported in recent days from a cold spell that hit parts of the nation, was up 0.75 cent to settle at 75.76 cents a gallon. `` I think the reaction to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> closure was totally irrational,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION>, said of the early rally. Prices jumped over concern that the closing of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> might disrupt oil shipments. But as most analysts noted only a small percentage of crude shipped to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> passes through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>.
