<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> condemned the use of force by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in speeches Wednesday before the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> but bogged down in haggling over procedures to vote on a resolution. Many of the members spoke out against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attacks in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> but they held fast to a rule requiring resolutions be submitted 24 hours before a vote can take place. They agreed to meet again Thursday. The resolution was suggested by <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabrera </PERSON>, a supporter of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noreiga </PERSON>, and was introduced by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cabrera </PERSON> called on the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> to condemn the `` brutal and criminal aggression'' against his country by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asked members to `` rally around'' the decision to send <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` We hope you will understand and support our action,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative <PERSON> Luigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON>. In a separate action, the Mexican government condemned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion, although it also denounced <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` The fight against international crime is not sufficient reason to intervene in a sovereign nation,'' the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government said in a statement issued through its embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s opinion, dialogue and negotiation continue to offer the best alternative in finding a peaceful solution to the situation.'' Among the usual allies condemning the use of force at the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> meeting were <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. Before the meeting began, the members met behind closed doors to discuss a letter sent by <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s newly sworn-in president, <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, asking that the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> recognize <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chewning </PERSON> <PERSON> Fabrega </PERSON> as his designated representative. The letter was telefaxed from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Southern Command. The <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> members decided to recognize <PERSON> Cabrera </PERSON>. They did not consider the issue of whether they recognized <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> and his government. `` The forces of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continue bombing,'' <PERSON> Cabrera </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> ministers at an emergency session called by <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to denounce the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion in his country. `` Under no circumstances will we accept some supposed leaders who are puppets imposed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said, referring to <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>'s government, which is recognized by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. The resolution before the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> asked members to condemn the use of force and demand a withdrawal of the troops. One of the ambassadors, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said shortly before the meeting began that the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> `` has to condemn this act, no matter how bad <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is. We ca n't condone violence.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Wednesday that he ordered troops into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to save American lives and bring <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to be tried on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would withdraw its invasion force as soon as possible. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is very pleased that the outlaw regime manipulated by <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has given way to a regime that reflects the democratic will of the people,'' <PERSON> Einaudi </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> members. `` Noriega increasingly acted in an unstable, unpredictable and dangerous manner.'' The Nicaraguan representative, <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, sided with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` It is an aberration to speak of democracy and carry out aggression,'' she said.
