<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two transport planes flew 108 servicemen wounded in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to military hospitals Wednesday, but three were dead on arrival and another died later, officials said. The first C-141 landed at <ORGANIZATION> Kelly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> at 11:37 a.m. with 43 soldiers aboard, including the three dead and the one who died shortly after arrival. The 39 wounded were taken to <ORGANIZATION> Wilford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at adjacent <ORGANIZATION> Lackland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, said Lt. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebner </PERSON>, a spokesman at <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. Some were well enough to take buses, and others were taken by ambulance, said <LOCATION> Lackland </LOCATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>. The second C-141 arrived at Kelly around 5:30 p.m. with 65 soldiers with `` serious to very critical'' injuries, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, another <LOCATION> Lackland </LOCATION> spokesman. `` The biggest and the most extensive injuries are gunshot-type wounds, schrapnel-type wounds, leg wounds, broken bones, this sort of thing,'' <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> said. Forty-one of the soldiers on the second flight were taken across town to <ORGANIZATION> Brooke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> said. The rest went to <LOCATION> Wilford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>. Another transport was expected later Wednesday, said <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, who was unsure how many wounded would be aboard. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> officials were told their base would be the sole reception point for wounded from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said 15 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen and a female civilian dependent were killed, one serviceman was missing and more than 100 were wounded.
