<HEAD>Some Grand Marnier Mechanical Ads Fail To Operate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reader's Digest, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Importers of Grand Marnier liqueur say the failure of about 10 percent of the 200,000 motorized holiday advertisements they placed in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> magazine earlier this month does n't discourage them. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Roux </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Carillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Importers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Teaneck </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, called the failure rate `` normal when introducing new technology'' and said he remained committed to trying new approaches to magazine ads. He estimated there have been about 500 complaints from readers who were disappointed that the highly-touted ad did n't work as they thought it should. The ad shows two birds with opposite ends of a ribbon in their beaks. The ribbon is draped around a liqueur bottle and as the birds alternately appear to fly higher, the bottle beneath them swings as if it were a bell. <PERSON> Roux </PERSON> said Monday in a telephone interview that reader surveys indicated 10 percent of the ads failed to operate as intended, and that the company was distributing replacements to those who ask for them. `` It's not a serious problem. We have mailed out 500 or so ads to people who said their ad did n't work,'' he said. He said the technology which made use of a battery and wire embedded beneath the pieces of cardboard used for the ad was sensitive and some systems were likely to get crushed in the binding and mailing processes. Some of the ads sent back were in working condition, but the readers apparently did n't wait long enough for the motorized action to begin, <PERSON> Roux </PERSON> said. He said a few people complained that the bell did n't ring _ but the ad was not designed to emit any sound. And other ads simply did n't work. From <PERSON> Roux </PERSON>'s perspective, getting a complaint is n't the worst thing that could happen. `` It shows they were interested by the ad,'' he said. <PERSON> Carillon </PERSON> spent about $ 750,000 on producing and placing the ad in 200,000 issues of the Dec. 11 edition of The New Yorker that were sent to subscribers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. The company has tried to make use of advances in technology for other magazine ads in the past, including singing and talking microchips for another of its products, Absolut vodka. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION>, said the magazine got `` about a dozen calls'' about Grand Marnier ads that failed to move. But he said he welcomed the attention that <PERSON> Roux </PERSON>'s ads bring to the magazine. `` We hope he does something as innovative next year,'' <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> said.
