<TEXT>
 In one stroke, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has become a significant international carrier through the $ 471 million purchase of Latin American and European routes and other assets from struggling <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The long-anticipated deal, announced Tuesday, increases American's Central and South American destinations from one city in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> to 20 in 15 countries. It also gives American its second <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> route in two days and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unused route authority from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. American Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON> said today the deal will allow <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> to `` fully realize our aspirations'' in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to gain badly needed cash as it tries to emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization. In a news conference in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> today, noted that the deal must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, but added, `` We certainly think it should be -LRB- approved -RRB- ... This is a very good transaction.'' American, besides being the No. 1 domestic airline, serves seven Mexican destinations and about 20 in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, plus has a growing presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where it has 5 percent of the market, and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. The agreement followed by one day American's $ 195 million purchase from <ORGA