<TEXT>
 The surprise attack by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> helped push the dollar higher today, but other financial markets reacted only mildly to the military intervention. On Wall Street, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average was up about 4 points to the 2,700 level by noon EST. But in the broader market, declining stocks slightly outnumbered advances on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond prices were unchanged to slightly higher in midday trading in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ordered troops into action following several days of tension triggered by the weekend shooting death of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officer in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> by defense forces controlled by Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Currency dealers said the dollar rose sharply against other major currencies just after the military action became known early today. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 144.23 yen, up 0.43 yen from Tuesday. It started the trading day at 143.92 yen and ranged between 143.90-144 .25 yen By midday in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the dollar was up against all currencies except the yen while gold prices moved higher. The dollar remained firm in early <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dealings. In times of international tension, investors often look for safe havens and usually turn to the dollar and precious metals. <PERSON> Gabriele </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, a trader with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </OR