<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 2 grafs of CenTrust comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State Comptroller <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> today began legal action to remove <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION>, claiming <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has used <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s largest savings and loan to support his `` opulent lifestyle.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> filed an administrative complaint that seeks removal of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> as chairman of the thrift. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has 21 days to either contest the complaint through a state hearing or comply with it. <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION> said it would oppose efforts to oust <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> and called <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' action was self-serving. `` This campaign is clearly aimed at generating favorable publicity for the comptroller and supporting his own re-election campaign whatever the cost to <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION>, its shareholders and its customers,'' the company said in a statement. The complaint charged that <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> used <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION> employees to perform personal services, charged the savings and loan for thousands of dollars in personal bills and engaged in other questionable financial transactions. `` <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> maintained an opulent lifestyle largely at the expense of the association, and generally treated a federally insured financial institution and public company as it if were his own public piggy bank,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said in the complaint. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s actions were unsound and unsafe business practices that violated his duty as an officer of a financial institution, the complaint charged. The complaint was filed 11 days after federal regulators, also citing <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION>'s lavish spending practices, ordered the institution to stop squandering its assets on fine art, sailboats, excessive executive salaries and other personal expenses. <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON>, spokesman for the comptroller's office, said the action today was highly unusual. `` But it's a fairly unusual institution,'' <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON> said. The complaint questioned <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s $ 4.8 million in salary between January 1988 and September of this year during a time when the thrift suffered operating losses of $ 76 million before taxes. <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION> also bought some $ 30 million in art in 1988 without <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' approval, spent thousands of dollars on executives' hotels bills and used high-prices limousines to ferry the thrift's officers around <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, the complaint charged The complaint also noted that $ 150,000 in <ORGANIZATION> CenTrust </ORGANIZATION> assets, including security equipment, video cameras, office supplies, telephones and air conditioners, were kept at <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s home on <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. When federal regulators made their charges earlier this month, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> issued a statement saying he had turned around a previously insolvent thrift and reduced its losses. `` We have achieved that without one penny of federal assistance while investing millions of dollars in developing a first-rate institution with the financial strength in place to meet the need of our customers,'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said at the time.
