<HEAD>Economy Grew At an Annual Rate of 3 Percent July Through September</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new to include Fed actions; picks up at pvs 10th
graf, In a</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy grew at an annual rate of 3 percent from July through September, the government said today, but analysts say it has slowed dramatically during the fourth quarter. The economic deterioration has led many anlaysts to urge the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to lower interest rates to stimulate the economy. The central bank did add money to the banking system late Tuesday, leading to the belief that it might permit interest rates to fall again. In its final report on third-quarter economic activity, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the gross national product was revised upward 0.3 percentage point from the 2.7 percent rate reported last month. Many economists had predicted no change from November in the figure released today. The change was attributed to another upward revision in net exports and a downward revision in personal consumption. The GNP is the nation's total output of goods and services and its broadest measure of economic health. The report bore good news for the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s goal of restraining inflation. A price index tied to the GNP rose at an annual rate of 2.9 percent during the July-September period, unchanged from last month's report. It is the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s high-interest policy that is blamed, in part, for the fourth-quarter sluggishness, particularly in the automobile and other manufacturing industries. The Federal Open Market Committee, the central bank's policymaking arm, met privately Monday and Tuesday to consider monetary policy but, as usual, did not announce whether it would permit rates to continue to fall However, the key federal funds rate, the interest banks charge each other for overnight loans, dropped to 8 7-16 percent from about 8 -LCB- percent late Tueday. Analysts said they expected a target of 8 \ percent for the rate Besides manufacturing sluggishness, other disruptions in fourth-quarter growth are expected from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> aircraft strike, the lingering effects of Hurricane Hugo and the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay-area </LOCATION> earthquake. In a companion report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said after-tax profits of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations fell 5.4 percent in the third quarter. That was a revision from the 7.2 percent decline reported last month. Corporate profits have dropped for three consecutive quarters. They were down 0.3 percent in the first quarter and 1.1 percent in the second. Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of all economic activity, was revised to show a 5.6 percent growth rate compared to the 6.2 percent gain reported last month. The various changes left the GNP expanding in the third quarter at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 4.16 trillion. Today's report was the third on the July-September GNP. In its initial estimate in October, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the third-quarter economy would grow at a 2.5 percent annual rate. Last month's initial revision was due mainly to better-than-expected trade performance. The September trade deficit, which hit a five-year low, was not available when the advance estimate was made in October. Today's revision reflects additional data that has become available. While the economy surprised many analysts with its 3 percent growth durin the first nine months of the year, it has declined significantly this quarter and some economists fear it will drop below 1 percent and perhaps even trip into a recession. The administration is forecasting a 2.7 percent growth rate for all of 1989. The fourth-quarter GNP would have to advance 1.6 percent to meet that goal. Much of the growth in the third quarter was attributed to robust automobile sales that were driven by sales incentives. Automakers dropped the incentives with the introduction of 1990 models in October and sales plummeted. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, noted that incentives are being restored and predicted a pickup in sales starting in January. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s high-interest policy is intended to curb inflation. As inflation appeared to moderate, the central bank has gradually eased interest rates since last June. But many economists say rates still are too high and are stifling growth, even threatening an end to an unprecedented seven years of peacetime growth. `` Fourth-quarter growth is about 0.8 percent,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON>, economic forecasting director at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He said growth in the first three months of 1990 will be about 1 percent. `` But I'm expecting a couple of prime rate cuts, and if we do n't see them we might turn our forecast to the negative,'' he said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, also suggested the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> should consider further easing interest rates `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will have to move to reduce interest rates in order to keep the economy going next year, but I think they're going to have to do it slowly,'' he said
