<HEAD>Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The energy futures market ended mixed in volatile trading Wednesday, erasing much of its earlier gains that stemmed from news of a sudden <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strike in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Prices for crude and refined petroleum products had been up sharply earlier in the trading day Wednesday on fears that the closure of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, following the surprise attack by American forces, might disrupt oil shipments. But analysts said the market had over-reacted. `` I think the reaction to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> closure was totally irrational,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION>, said. `` Our crude oil supplies simply wo n't be disrupted.'' Analysts said that only a small percentage of crude shipped to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> passes through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> because the waterway is too small to handle large tankers. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the leading grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, was down 7 cents to settle at $ 21.21 per 42-gallon barrel. The contract was up 11 cents on Tuesday. Among refined petroleum products, the January wholesale home heating oil contract, supported in recent days from a cold spell that hit parts of the nation, rose 0.75 cent to settle at 75.76 cents a gallon. On Tuesday, the contract gained 0.35 cent. January wholesale unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.58 cent in the previous session, ended 0.71 cent lower to 53.22 cents a gallon.
