<HEAD>Stock Offering Withdrawal Shows Market Weakness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 European food concern <ORGANIZATION> TLC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beatrice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to scrap a public stock offering to raise up to $ 194 million reflects a general weakness in the market for new issues, analysts said Wednesday. The move also postponed what would have been two firsts: the first former <ORGANIZATION> Beatrice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> holding to go public since a $ 6 billion takeover in 1986 and the first black-owned company to be listed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. TLC <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> on Tuesday canceled the offering of 18.5 million shares of stock priced from $ 9 to $ 10.50 a share. A successful offering would have raised between $ 167 million and $ 194 million. The company, controlled by investor <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, cited weak market conditions and a lack of interest from institutional investors in canceling the plan to offer a 35 percent interest to the public. `` It's not what I would call a hot new issues market,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fosback </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Econometric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, which analyzes new stock issues. `` Offerings tend to be overpriced.'' `` My sense is that there is very little demand for offerings from individual investors, and institutions are dominating the market,'' said <PERSON> Fosback </PERSON>, who did not recommend the TLC <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> issue. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumbach </PERSON>, a new issues analyst for <ORGANIZ