ions on weather-driven worries about tightening supplies. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 10 cents lower with February at $ 21.21 a barrel; heating oil was .59 cent lower to .75 cent higher with January at 75.76 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to .71 cent lower with January at 53.22 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, paced by moderate losses in the soybean market linked partly to the closing of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Wheat futures settled unchanged to 1 \ cents lower with March at $ 4.13 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1 \ cents lower with March at $ 2.38 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 1 cent lower with March at $ 1.52 \ a bushel; soybeans were 3 -RCB- cents to 6 cents lower with January at $ 5.73 -RCB- Livestock and meat futures finished lower, led by limit losses in the pork belly market amid disappointment over the government's slow pace in buying pork bellies to ship to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and expectations that monthly <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report due out on Thursday will show a net increase in supplies of frozen bellies Live cattle settled .10 cent to .55 cent lower with December at 78.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .15 cent lower with January at 84.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .27 cent to .85 cent lower with December at 52.67 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.90 cents to 2 cents lower with February at 49.60 cents a pound.
